  version: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 51ee3e37f5ded7941ab6216610f6fc67, type: 2}
  description: 
  chapters:
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Solomon Asks for Wisdom'
      title: Solomon Asks for Wisdom
      number: 1
      content: '  Solomon son of David took firm control of his kingdom, for the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> his God was with him and made him very powerful.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Solomon called together all the leaders of Israel\u2014the generals
        and captains of the army,[[COMMENT(0)]] the judges, and all the political
        and clan leaders. "
      comments:
      - number: '1:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the commanders of thousands and of hundreds.</b>
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Then he led the entire assembly to the place of worship in Gibeon,
        for God\u2019s Tabernacle[[COMMENT(0)]] was located there. (This was the
        Tabernacle that Moses, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s servant, had
        made in the wilderness.)  "
      comments:
      - number: '1:3 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Tent of Meeting; </b>also in 1:6, 13.
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'David had already moved the Ark of God from Kiriath-jearim to the
        tent he had prepared for it in Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'But the bronze altar made by Bezalel son of Uri and grandson of Hur
        was there[[COMMENT(0)]] at Gibeon in front of the Tabernacle of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        So Solomon and the people gathered in front of it to consult the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.[[COMMENT(1)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '1:5a '
        content: As in Greek version and Latin Vulgate, and some Hebrew manuscripts;
          Masoretic Text reads <b>he placed.</b>
      - number: '1:5b '
        content: Hebrew <b>to consult him.</b>
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "There in front of the Tabernacle, Solomon went up to the bronze altar
        in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s presence and sacrificed 1,000 burnt
        offerings on it.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "That night God appeared to Solomon and said, \u201CWhat do you want?
        Ask, and I will give it to you!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Solomon replied to God, \u201CYou showed great and faithful love
        to David, my father, and now you have made me king in his place. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God, please continue to keep your promise
        to David my father, for you have made me king over a people as numerous as
        the dust of the earth! '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Give me the wisdom and knowledge to lead them properly,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        for who could possibly govern this great people of yours?\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '1:10 '
        content: Hebrew <b>to go out and come in before this people.</b>
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "God said to Solomon, \u201CBecause your greatest desire is to help
        your people, and you did not ask for wealth, riches, fame, or even the death
        of your enemies or a long life, but rather you asked for wisdom and knowledge
        to properly govern my people\u2014 "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "I will certainly give you the wisdom and knowledge you requested.
        But I will also give you wealth, riches, and fame such as no other king has
        had before you or will ever have in the future!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Then Solomon returned to Jerusalem from the Tabernacle at the place
        of worship in Gibeon, and he reigned over Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Solomon built up a huge force of chariots and horses.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        He had 1,400 chariots and 12,000 horses. He stationed some of them in the
        chariot cities and some near him in Jerusalem. '
      comments:
      - number: '1:14 '
        content: Or <b>charioteers; </b>also in 1:14b.
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'The king made silver and gold as plentiful in Jerusalem as stone.
        And valuable cedar timber was as common as the sycamore-fig trees that grow
        in the foothills of Judah.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '1:15 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Shephelah.</b>
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Solomon\u2019s horses were imported from Egypt[[COMMENT(0)]] and
        from Cilicia[[COMMENT(1)]]; the king\u2019s traders acquired them from Cilicia
        at the standard price. "
      comments:
      - number: '1:16a '
        content: Possibly <b>Muzur, </b>a district near Cilicia; also in 1:17.
      - number: '1:16b '
        content: Hebrew <b>Kue, </b>probably another name for Cilicia.
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: At that time chariots from Egypt could be purchased for 600 pieces
        of silver,[[COMMENT(0)]] and horses for 150 pieces of silver.[[COMMENT(1)]]
        They were then exported to the kings of the Hittites and the kings of Aram.
      comments:
      - number: '1:17a '
        content: Hebrew <b>600 [shekels] of silver, </b>about 15 pounds or 6.8 kilograms
          in weight.
      - number: '1:17b '
        content: Hebrew <b>150 [shekels], </b>about 3.8 pounds or 1.7 kilograms in
          weight.
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Preparations for Building the Temple'
      title: Preparations for Building the Temple
      number: 1
      content: '    [[COMMENT(0)]]Solomon decided to build a Temple to honor the
        name of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, and also a royal palace for himself. '
      comments:
      - number: '2:1 '
        content: '  Verse 2:1 is numbered 1:18 in Hebrew text.  '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: '[[COMMENT(0)]]He enlisted a force of 70,000 laborers, 80,000 men
        to quarry stone in the hill country, and 3,600 foremen.  '
      comments:
      - number: '2:2 '
        content: Verses 2:2-18 are numbered 2:1-17 in Hebrew text.
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Solomon also sent this message to King Hiram[[COMMENT(0)]] at Tyre:\u201CSend
        me cedar logs as you did for my father, David, when he was building his palace. "
      comments:
      - number: '2:3 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Huram, </b>a variant spelling of Hiram; also in 2:11.
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'I am about to build a Temple to honor the name of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        my God. It will be a place set apart to burn fragrant incense before him,
        to display the special sacrificial bread, and to sacrifice burnt offerings
        each morning and evening, on the Sabbaths, at new moon celebrations, and
        at the other appointed festivals of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> our God.
        He has commanded Israel to do these things forever.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "\u201CThis must be a magnificent Temple because our God is greater
        than all other gods. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'But who can really build him a worthy home? Not even the highest
        heavens can contain him! So who am I to consider building a Temple for him,
        except as a place to burn sacrifices to him?  '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "\u201CSo send me a master craftsman who can work with gold, silver,
        bronze, and iron, as well as with purple, scarlet, and blue cloth. He must
        be a skilled engraver who can work with the craftsmen of Judah and Jerusalem
        who were selected by my father, David.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201CAlso send me cedar, cypress, and red sandalwood[[COMMENT(0)]]
        logs from Lebanon, for I know that your men are without equal at cutting
        timber in Lebanon. I will send my men to help them. "
      comments:
      - number: '2:8 '
        content: Or <b>juniper; </b>Hebrew reads <b>algum, </b>perhaps a variant
          spelling of <b>almug; </b>compare 9:10-11 and parallel text at 1 Kgs 10:11-12.
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'An immense amount of timber will be needed, for the Temple I am going
        to build will be very large and magnificent. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "In payment for your woodcutters, I will send 100,000 bushels of crushed
        wheat, 100,000 bushels of barley,[[COMMENT(0)]] 110,000 gallons of wine,
        and 110,000 gallons of olive oil.[[COMMENT(1)]]\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '2:10a '
        content: Hebrew <b>20,000 cors </b>[4,400 kiloliters] <b>of crushed wheat,
          20,000 cors of barley.</b>
      - number: '2:10b '
        content: Hebrew <b>20,000 baths </b>[420 kiloliters] <b>of wine, and 20,000
          baths of olive oil.</b>
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "King Hiram sent this letter of reply to Solomon:\u201CIt is because
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> loves his people that he has made you their
        king! "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'Praise the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel, who made
        the heavens and the earth! He has given King David a wise son, gifted with
        skill and understanding, who will build a Temple for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and a royal palace for himself.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201CI am sending you a master craftsman named Huram-abi, who is
        extremely talented. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'His mother is from the tribe of Dan in Israel, and his father is
        from Tyre. He is skillful at making things from gold, silver, bronze, and
        iron, and he also works with stone and wood. He can work with purple, blue,
        and scarlet cloth and fine linen. He is also an engraver and can follow any
        design given to him. He will work with your craftsmen and those appointed
        by my lord David, your father.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "\u201CSend along the wheat, barley, olive oil, and wine that my lord
        has mentioned. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "We will cut whatever timber you need from the Lebanon mountains and
        will float the logs in rafts down the coast of the Mediterranean Sea[[COMMENT(0)]]
        to Joppa. From there you can transport the logs up to Jerusalem.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '2:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the sea.</b>
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Solomon took a census of all foreigners in the land of Israel, like
        the census his father had taken, and he counted 153,600. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: He assigned 70,000 of them as common laborers, 80,000 as quarry workers
        in the hill country, and 3,600 as foremen.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Solomon Builds the Temple'
      title: Solomon Builds the Temple
      number: 1
      content: '  So Solomon began to build the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        in Jerusalem on Mount Moriah, where the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had appeared
        to David, his father. The Temple was built on the threshing floor of Araunah[[COMMENT(0)]]
        the Jebusite, the site that David had selected. '
      comments:
      - number: '3:1 '
        content: Hebrew reads <b>Ornan, </b>a variant spelling of Araunah; compare
          2 Sam 24:16.
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "The construction began in midspring,[[COMMENT(0)]] during the fourth
        year of Solomon\u2019s reign.  "
      comments:
      - number: '3:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>on the second [day] of the second month. </b>This day
          of the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar occurred in April or May.
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'These are the dimensions Solomon used for the foundation of the Temple
        of God (using the old standard of measurement).[[COMMENT(0)]] It was 90 feet
        long and 30 feet wide.[[COMMENT(1)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '3:3a '
        content: "The \u201Cold standard of measurement\u201D was a cubit equal to
          18 inches [46 centimeters]. The new standard was a cubit of approximately
          21 inches [53 centimeters]."
      - number: '3:3b '
        content: Hebrew <b>60 cubits </b>[27.6 meters] <b>long and 20 cubits </b>[9.2
          meters] <b>wide.</b>
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'The entry room at the front of the Temple was 30 feet[[COMMENT(0)]]
        wide, running across the entire width of the Temple, and 30 feet[[COMMENT(1)]]
        high. He overlaid the inside with pure gold.  '
      comments:
      - number: '3:4a '
        content: Hebrew <b>20 cubits </b>[9.2 meters]; also in 3:8, 11, 13.
      - number: '3:4b '
        content: As in some Greek and Syriac manuscripts, which read <b>20 cubits
          </b>[9.2 meters]; Hebrew reads <b>120 [cubits], </b>which is 180 feet or
          55 meters.
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'He paneled the main room of the Temple with cypress wood, overlaid
        it with fine gold, and decorated it with carvings of palm trees and chains. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'He decorated the walls of the Temple with beautiful jewels and with
        gold from the land of Parvaim. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'He overlaid the beams, thresholds, walls, and doors throughout the
        Temple with gold, and he carved figures of cherubim on the walls.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'He made the Most Holy Place 30 feet wide, corresponding to the width
        of the Temple, and 30 feet deep. He overlaid its interior with 23 tons[[COMMENT(0)]]
        of fine gold. '
      comments:
      - number: '3:8 '
        content: Hebrew <b>600 talents </b>[20.4 metric tons].
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'The gold nails that were used weighed 20 ounces[[COMMENT(0)]] each.
        He also overlaid the walls of the upper rooms with gold.  '
      comments:
      - number: '3:9 '
        content: Hebrew <b>50 shekels </b>[570 grams].
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'He made two figures shaped like cherubim, overlaid them with gold,
        and placed them in the Most Holy Place. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'The total wingspan of the two cherubim standing side by side was
        30 feet. One wing of the first figure was 7-1/2 feet[[COMMENT(0)]] long,
        and it touched the Temple wall. The other wing, also 7-1/2 feet long, touched
        one of the wings of the second figure. '
      comments:
      - number: '3:11 '
        content: Hebrew <b>5 cubits </b>[2.3 meters]; also in 3:11b, 12, 15.
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'In the same way, the second figure had one wing 7-1/2 feet long that
        touched the opposite wall. The other wing, also 7-1/2 feet long, touched
        the wing of the first figure. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'So the wingspan of the two cherubim side by side was 30 feet. They
        stood on their feet and faced out toward the main room of the Temple.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Across the entrance of the Most Holy Place he hung a curtain made
        of fine linen, decorated with blue, purple, and scarlet thread and embroidered
        with figures of cherubim.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'For the front of the Temple, he made two pillars that were 27 feet[[COMMENT(0)]]
        tall, each topped by a capital extending upward another 7-1/2 feet. '
      comments:
      - number: '3:15 '
        content: As in Syriac version (see also 1 Kgs 7:15; 2 Kgs 25:17; Jer 52:21),
          which reads <b>18 cubits </b>[8.3 meters]; Hebrew reads <b>35 cubits, </b>which
          is 52.5 feet or 16.5 meters.
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'He made a network of interwoven chains[[COMMENT(0)]] and used them
        to decorate the tops of the pillars. He also made 100 decorative pomegranates
        and attached them to the chains. '
      comments:
      - number: '3:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>He made chains in the inner sanctuary. </b>The meaning
          of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: Then he set up the two pillars at the entrance of the Temple, one
        to the south of the entrance and the other to the north. He named the one
        on the south Jakin, and the one on the north Boaz.[[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: '3:17 '
        content: "<b>Jakin </b>probably means \u201Che establishes\u201D; <b>Boaz
          </b>probably means \u201Cin him is strength.\u201D"
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Furnishings for the Temple'
      title: Furnishings for the Temple
      number: 1
      content: '  Solomon[[COMMENT(0)]] also made a bronze altar 30 feet long, 30
        feet wide, and 15 feet high.[[COMMENT(1)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '4:1a '
        content: Or <b>Huram-abi; </b>Hebrew reads <b>He.</b>
      - number: '4:1b '
        content: Hebrew <b>20 cubits </b>[9.2 meters] <b>long, 20 cubits wide, and
          10 cubits </b>[4.6 meters] <b>high.</b>
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Then he cast a great round basin, 15 feet across from rim to rim,
        called the Sea. It was 7-1/2 feet deep and about 45 feet in circumference.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '4:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>10 cubits </b>[4.6 meters] <b>across . . . 5 cubits </b>[2.3
          meters] <b>deep and 30 cubits </b>[13.8 meters] <b>in circumference.</b>
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'It was encircled just below its rim by two rows of figures that resembled
        oxen. There were about six oxen per foot[[COMMENT(0)]] all the way around,
        and they were cast as part of the basin.  '
      comments:
      - number: '4:3 '
        content: Or <b>20 oxen per meter; </b>Hebrew reads <b>10 per cubit.</b>
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'The Sea was placed on a base of twelve bronze oxen, all facing outward.
        Three faced north, three faced west, three faced south, and three faced east,
        and the Sea rested on them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'The walls of the Sea were about three inches[[COMMENT(0)]] thick,
        and its rim flared out like a cup and resembled a water lily blossom. It
        could hold about 16,500 gallons[[COMMENT(1)]] of water.  '
      comments:
      - number: '4:5a '
        content: Hebrew <b>a handbreadth </b>[8 centimeters].
      - number: '4:5b '
        content: Hebrew <b>3,000 baths </b>[63 kiloliters].
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'He also made ten smaller basins for washing the utensils for the
        burnt offerings. He set five on the south side and five on the north. But
        the priests washed themselves in the Sea.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'He then cast ten gold lampstands according to the specifications
        that had been given, and he put them in the Temple. Five were placed against
        the south wall, and five were placed against the north wall.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'He also built ten tables and placed them in the Temple, five along
        the south wall and five along the north wall. Then he molded 100 gold basins.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'He then built a courtyard for the priests, and also the large outer
        courtyard. He made doors for the courtyard entrances and overlaid them with
        bronze. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'The great bronze basin called the Sea was placed near the southeast
        corner of the Temple.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Huram-abi also made the necessary washbasins, shovels, and bowls.So
        at last Huram-abi completed everything King Solomon had assigned him to make
        for the Temple of God:  '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'the two pillars;the two bowl-shaped capitals on top of the pillars;the
        two networks of interwoven chains that decorated the capitals;  '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'the 400 pomegranates that hung from the chains on the capitals (two
        rows of pomegranates for each of the chain networks that decorated the capitals
        on top of the pillars);  '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'the water carts holding the basins;  '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'the Sea and the twelve oxen under it;  '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'the ash buckets, the shovels, the meat hooks, and all the related
        articles.Huram-abi made all these things of burnished bronze for the Temple
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, just as King Solomon had directed. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'The king had them cast in clay molds in the Jordan Valley between
        Succoth and Zarethan.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '4:17 '
        content: As in parallel text at 1 Kgs 7:46; Hebrew reads <b>Zeredah.</b>
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Solomon used such great quantities of bronze that its weight could
        not be determined.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'Solomon also made all the furnishings for the Temple of God:the gold
        altar;the tables for the Bread of the Presence;  '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'the lampstands and their lamps of solid gold, to burn in front of
        the Most Holy Place as prescribed;  '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "the flower decorations, lamps, and tongs\u2014all of the purest gold;  "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "the lamp snuffers, bowls, ladles, and incense burners\u2014all of
        solid gold;the doors for the entrances to the Most Holy Place and the main
        room of the Temple, overlaid with gold."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Ark Brought to the Temple'
      title: The Ark Brought to the Temple
      number: 1
      content: "  So Solomon finished all his work on the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        Then he brought all the gifts his father, David, had dedicated\u2014the silver,
        the gold, and the various articles\u2014and he stored them in the treasuries
        of the Temple of God.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Solomon then summoned to Jerusalem the elders of Israel and all the
        heads of tribes\u2014the leaders of the ancestral families of Israel. They
        were to bring the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Covenant
        to the Temple from its location in the City of David, also known as Zion. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'So all the men of Israel assembled before the king at the annual
        Festival of Shelters, which is held in early autumn.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '5:3 '
        content: Hebrew <b>at the festival that is in the seventh month. </b>The
          Festival of Shelters began on the fifteenth day of the seventh month of
          the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar. This day occurred in late September,
          October, or early November.
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'When all the elders of Israel arrived, the Levites picked up the
        Ark. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'The priests and Levites brought up the Ark along with the special
        tent[[COMMENT(0)]] and all the sacred items that had been in it. '
      comments:
      - number: '5:5 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Tent of Meeting; </b>i.e., the tent mentioned in 2
          Sam 6:17 and 1 Chr 16:1.
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'There, before the Ark, King Solomon and the entire community of Israel
        sacrificed so many sheep, goats, and cattle that no one could keep count!  '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Then the priests carried the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Covenant into the inner sanctuary of the Temple\u2014the Most Holy Place\u2014and
        placed it beneath the wings of the cherubim. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'The cherubim spread their wings over the Ark, forming a canopy over
        the Ark and its carrying poles. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'These poles were so long that their ends could be seen from the Holy
        Place,[[COMMENT(0)]] which is in front of the Most Holy Place, but not from
        the outside. They are still there to this day. '
      comments:
      - number: '5:9 '
        content: As in some Hebrew manuscripts and Greek version (see also 1 Kgs
          8:8); Masoretic Text reads <b>from the Ark.</b>
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Nothing was in the Ark except the two stone tablets that Moses had
        placed in it at Mount Sinai,[[COMMENT(0)]] where the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        made a covenant with the people of Israel when they left Egypt.  '
      comments:
      - number: '5:10 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Horeb, </b>another name for Sinai.
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Then the priests left the Holy Place. All the priests who were present
        had purified themselves, whether or not they were on duty that day. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "And the Levites who were musicians\u2014Asaph, Heman, Jeduthun, and
        all their sons and brothers\u2014were dressed in fine linen robes and stood
        at the east side of the altar playing cymbals, lyres, and harps. They were
        joined by 120 priests who were playing trumpets. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "The trumpeters and singers performed together in unison to praise
        and give thanks to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. Accompanied by trumpets,
        cymbals, and other instruments, they raised their voices and praised the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> with these words:\u201CHe is good!His faithful
        love endures forever!\u201DAt that moment a thick cloud filled the Temple
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: The priests could not continue their service because of the cloud,
        for the glorious presence of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> filled the Temple
        of God.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Solomon Praises the '
      title: 'Solomon Praises the '
      number: 1
      content: "<smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>  Then Solomon prayed, \u201CO <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        you have said that you would live in a thick cloud of darkness. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Now I have built a glorious Temple for you, a place where you can
        live forever!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Then the king turned around to the entire community of Israel standing
        before him and gave this blessing: '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "\u201CPraise the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel,
        who has kept the promise he made to my father, David. For he told my father, "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "\u2018From the day I brought my people out of the land of Egypt,
        I have never chosen a city among any of the tribes of Israel as the place
        where a Temple should be built to honor my name. Nor have I chosen a king
        to lead my people Israel. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "But now I have chosen Jerusalem as the place for my name to be honored,
        and I have chosen David to be king over my people Israel.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Then Solomon said, \u201CMy father, David, wanted to build this Temple
        to honor the name of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> told him, \u2018You wanted to
        build the Temple to honor my name. Your intention is good, "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "but you are not the one to do it. One of your own sons will build
        the Temple to honor me.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201CAnd now the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has fulfilled the promise
        he made, for I have become king in my father\u2019s place, and now I sit
        on the throne of Israel, just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> promised.
        I have built this Temple to honor the name of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel. "
      comments: []
    - name: "11: Solomon\u2019s Prayer of Dedication"
      title: "Solomon\u2019s Prayer of Dedication"
      number: 11
      content: "There I have placed the Ark, which contains the covenant that the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> made with the people of Israel.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'Then Solomon stood before the altar of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        in front of the entire community of Israel, and he lifted his hands in prayer. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Now Solomon had made a bronze platform 7-1/2 feet long, 7-1/2 feet
        wide, and 4-1/2 feet high[[COMMENT(0)]] and had placed it at the center of
        the Temple\u2019s outer courtyard. He stood on the platform, and then he
        knelt in front of the entire community of Israel and lifted his hands toward
        heaven. "
      comments:
      - number: '6:13 '
        content: Hebrew <b>5 cubits </b>[2.3 meters] <b>long, 5 cubits wide, and
          3 cubits </b>[1.4 meters] <b>high.</b>
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "He prayed,\u201CO <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, God of Israel, there
        is no God like you in all of heaven and earth. You keep your covenant and
        show unfailing love to all who walk before you in wholehearted devotion. "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'You have kept your promise to your servant David, my father. You
        made that promise with your own mouth, and with your own hands you have fulfilled
        it today.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "\u201CAnd now, O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, God of Israel, carry
        out the additional promise you made to your servant David, my father. For
        you said to him, \u2018If your descendants guard their behavior and faithfully
        follow my Law as you have done, one of them will always sit on the throne
        of Israel.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Now, O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, God of Israel, fulfill this promise
        to your servant David.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "\u201CBut will God really live on earth among people? Why, even the
        highest heavens cannot contain you. How much less this Temple I have built! "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'Nevertheless, listen to my prayer and my plea, O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        my God. Hear the cry and the prayer that your servant is making to you. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'May you watch over this Temple day and night, this place where you
        have said you would put your name. May you always hear the prayers I make
        toward this place. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'May you hear the humble and earnest requests from me and your people
        Israel when we pray toward this place. Yes, hear us from heaven where you
        live, and when you hear, forgive.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "\u201CIf someone wrongs another person and is required to take an
        oath of innocence in front of your altar at this Temple, "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "then hear from heaven and judge between your servants\u2014the accuser
        and the accused. Pay back the guilty as they deserve. Acquit the innocent
        because of their innocence.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "\u201CIf your people Israel are defeated by their enemies because
        they have sinned against you, and if they turn back and acknowledge your
        name and pray to you here in this Temple, "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'then hear from heaven and forgive the sin of your people Israel and
        return them to this land you gave to them and to their ancestors.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "\u201CIf the skies are shut up and there is no rain because your
        people have sinned against you, and if they pray toward this Temple and acknowledge
        your name and turn from their sins because you have punished them, "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'then hear from heaven and forgive the sins of your servants, your
        people Israel. Teach them to follow the right path, and send rain on your
        land that you have given to your people as their special possession.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "\u201CIf there is a famine in the land or a plague or crop disease
        or attacks of locusts or caterpillars, or if your people\u2019s enemies are
        in the land besieging their towns\u2014whatever disaster or disease there
        is\u2014 "
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'and if your people Israel pray about their troubles or sorrow, raising
        their hands toward this Temple, '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'then hear from heaven where you live, and forgive. Give your people
        what their actions deserve, for you alone know each human heart. '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'Then they will fear you and walk in your ways as long as they live
        in the land you gave to our ancestors.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "\u201CIn the future, foreigners who do not belong to your people
        Israel will hear of you. They will come from distant lands when they hear
        of your great name and your strong hand and your powerful arm. And when they
        pray toward this Temple, "
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'then hear from heaven where you live, and grant what they ask of
        you. In this way, all the people of the earth will come to know and fear
        you, just as your own people Israel do. They, too, will know that this Temple
        I have built honors your name.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "\u201CIf your people go out where you send them to fight their enemies,
        and if they pray to you by turning toward this city you have chosen and toward
        this Temple I have built to honor your name, "
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: 'then hear their prayers from heaven and uphold their cause.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "\u201CIf they sin against you\u2014and who has never sinned?\u2014you
        might become angry with them and let their enemies conquer them and take
        them captive to a foreign land far away or near. "
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "But in that land of exile, they might turn to you in repentance and
        pray, \u2018We have sinned, done evil, and acted wickedly.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "If they turn to you with their whole heart and soul in the land of
        their captivity and pray toward the land you gave to their ancestors\u2014toward
        this city you have chosen, and toward this Temple I have built to honor your
        name\u2014 "
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: 'then hear their prayers and their petitions from heaven where you
        live, and uphold their cause. Forgive your people who have sinned against
        you.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: "\u201CO my God, may your eyes be open and your ears attentive to
        all the prayers made to you in this place.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: "\u201CAnd now arise, O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God, and enter
        your resting place,along with the Ark, the symbol of your power.May your
        priests, O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God, be clothed with salvation;may
        your loyal servants rejoice in your goodness.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: "O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God, do not reject the king you have
        anointed.Remember your unfailing love for your servant David.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Dedication of the Temple'
      title: The Dedication of the Temple
      number: 1
      content: '  When Solomon finished praying, fire flashed down from heaven and
        burned up the burnt offerings and sacrifices, and the glorious presence of
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> filled the Temple. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'The priests could not enter the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        because the glorious presence of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> filled it. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "When all the people of Israel saw the fire coming down and the glorious
        presence of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> filling the Temple, they fell
        face down on the ground and worshiped and praised the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        saying,\u201CHe is good!His faithful love endures forever!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'Then the king and all the people offered sacrifices to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'King Solomon offered a sacrifice of 22,000 cattle and 120,000 sheep
        and goats. And so the king and all the people dedicated the Temple of God. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "The priests took their assigned positions, and so did the Levites
        who were singing, \u201CHis faithful love endures forever!\u201D They accompanied
        the singing with music from the instruments King David had made for praising
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. Across from the Levites, the priests blew
        the trumpets, while all Israel stood.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Solomon then consecrated the central area of the courtyard in front
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple. He offered burnt offerings
        and the fat of peace offerings there, because the bronze altar he had built
        could not hold all the burnt offerings, grain offerings, and sacrificial
        fat.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'For the next seven days Solomon and all Israel celebrated the Festival
        of Shelters.[[COMMENT(0)]] A large congregation had gathered from as far
        away as Lebo-hamath in the north and the Brook of Egypt in the south. '
      comments:
      - number: '7:8 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the festival </b>(also in 7:9); see note on 5:3.
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'On the eighth day they had a closing ceremony, for they had celebrated
        the dedication of the altar for seven days and the Festival of Shelters for
        seven days. '
      comments: []
    - name: "10: The \u2019s Response to Solomon"
      title: "The \u2019s Response to Solomon"
      number: 10
      content: 'Then at the end of the celebration,[[COMMENT(0)]] Solomon sent the
        people home. They were all joyful and glad because the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had been so good to David and to Solomon and to his people Israel.<smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>  '
      comments:
      - number: '7:10 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Then on the twenty-third day of the seventh month. </b>This
          day of the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar occurred in October or early November.
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'So Solomon finished the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        as well as the royal palace. He completed everything he had planned to do
        in the construction of the Temple and the palace. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Then one night the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> appeared to Solomon
        and said,\u201CI have heard your prayer and have chosen this Temple as the
        place for making sacrifices. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'At times I might shut up the heavens so that no rain falls, or command
        grasshoppers to devour your crops, or send plagues among you. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Then if my people who are called by my name will humble themselves
        and pray and seek my face and turn from their wicked ways, I will hear from
        heaven and will forgive their sins and restore their land. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'My eyes will be open and my ears attentive to every prayer made in
        this place. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "For I have chosen this Temple and set it apart to be holy\u2014a
        place where my name will be honored forever. I will always watch over it,
        for it is dear to my heart.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "\u201CAs for you, if you faithfully follow me as David your father
        did, obeying all my commands, decrees, and regulations, "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "then I will establish the throne of your dynasty. For I made this
        covenant with your father, David, when I said, \u2018One of your descendants
        will always rule over Israel.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "\u201CBut if you or your descendants abandon me and disobey the decrees
        and commands I have given you, and if you serve and worship other gods, "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'then I will uproot the people from this land that I have given them.
        I will reject this Temple that I have made holy to honor my name. I will
        make it an object of mockery and ridicule among the nations. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "And though this Temple is impressive now, all who pass by will be
        appalled. They will ask, \u2018Why did the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> do
        such terrible things to this land and to this Temple?\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "\u201CAnd the answer will be, \u2018Because his people abandoned
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of their ancestors, who brought
        them out of Egypt, and they worshiped other gods instead and bowed down to
        them. That is why he has brought all these disasters on them.\u2019\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Solomon\u2019s Many Achievements"
      title: "Solomon\u2019s Many Achievements"
      number: 1
      content: "  It took Solomon twenty years to build the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple and his own royal palace. At the end of that time, "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Solomon turned his attention to rebuilding the towns that King Hiram[[COMMENT(0)]]
        had given him, and he settled Israelites in them.  '
      comments:
      - number: '8:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Huram, </b>a variant spelling of Hiram; also in 8:18.
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Solomon also fought against the town of Hamath-zobah and conquered
        it. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'He rebuilt Tadmor in the wilderness and built towns in the region
        of Hamath as supply centers. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'He fortified the towns of Upper Beth-horon and Lower Beth-horon,
        rebuilding their walls and installing barred gates. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'He also rebuilt Baalath and other supply centers and constructed
        towns where his chariots and horses[[COMMENT(0)]] could be stationed. He
        built everything he desired in Jerusalem and Lebanon and throughout his entire
        realm.  '
      comments:
      - number: '8:6 '
        content: Or <b>and charioteers.</b>
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'There were still some people living in the land who were not Israelites,
        including the Hittites, Amorites, Perizzites, Hivites, and Jebusites. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'These were descendants of the nations whom the people of Israel had
        not destroyed. So Solomon conscripted them for his labor force, and they
        serve as forced laborers to this day. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'But Solomon did not conscript any of the Israelites for his labor
        force. Instead, he assigned them to serve as fighting men, officers in his
        army, commanders of his chariots, and charioteers. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'King Solomon appointed 250 of them to supervise the people.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Solomon moved his wife, Pharaoh\u2019s daughter, from the City of
        David to the new palace he had built for her. He said, \u201CMy wife must
        not live in King David\u2019s palace, for the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has been there, and it is holy ground.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'Then Solomon presented burnt offerings to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        on the altar he had built for him in front of the entry room of the Temple. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "He offered the sacrifices for the Sabbaths, the new moon festivals,
        and the three annual festivals\u2014the Passover celebration, the Festival
        of Harvest,[[COMMENT(0)]] and the Festival of Shelters\u2014as Moses had
        commanded.  "
      comments:
      - number: '8:13 '
        content: Or <b>Festival of Weeks.</b>
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'In assigning the priests to their duties, Solomon followed the regulations
        of his father, David. He also assigned the Levites to lead the people in
        praise and to assist the priests in their daily duties. And he assigned the
        gatekeepers to their gates by their divisions, following the commands of
        David, the man of God. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Solomon did not deviate in any way from David\u2019s commands concerning
        the priests and Levites and the treasuries.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'So Solomon made sure that all the work related to building the Temple
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was carried out, from the day its foundation
        was laid to the day of its completion.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Later Solomon went to Ezion-geber and Elath,[[COMMENT(0)]] ports
        along the shore of the Red Sea[[COMMENT(1)]] in the land of Edom. '
      comments:
      - number: '8:17a '
        content: As in Greek version (see also 2 Kgs 14:22; 16:6); Hebrew reads <b>Eloth,
          </b>a variant spelling of Elath.
      - number: '8:17b '
        content: As in parallel text at 1 Kgs 9:26; Hebrew reads <b>the sea.</b>
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Hiram sent him ships commanded by his own officers and manned by
        experienced crews of sailors. These ships sailed to Ophir with Solomon\u2019s
        men and brought back to Solomon almost seventeen tons[[COMMENT(0)]] of gold."
      comments:
      - number: '8:18 '
        content: Hebrew <b>450 talents </b>[15.3 metric tons].
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Visit of the Queen of Sheba'
      title: Visit of the Queen of Sheba
      number: 1
      content: "  When the queen of Sheba heard of Solomon\u2019s fame, she came
        to Jerusalem to test him with hard questions. She arrived with a large group
        of attendants and a great caravan of camels loaded with spices, large quantities
        of gold, and precious jewels. When she met with Solomon, she talked with
        him about everything she had on her mind. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Solomon had answers for all her questions; nothing was too hard for
        him to explain to her. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'When the queen of Sheba realized how wise Solomon was, and when she
        saw the palace he had built, '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'she was overwhelmed. She was also amazed at the food on his tables,
        the organization of his officials and their splendid clothing, the cup-bearers
        and their robes, and the burnt offerings[[COMMENT(0)]] Solomon made at the
        Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments:
      - number: '9:4 '
        content: As in Greek and Syriac versions (see also 1 Kgs 10:5); Hebrew reads
          <b>and the ascent.</b>
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "She exclaimed to the king, \u201CEverything I heard in my country
        about your achievements[[COMMENT(0)]] and wisdom is true! "
      comments:
      - number: '9:5 '
        content: Hebrew <b>your words.</b>
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "I didn\u2019t believe what was said until I arrived here and saw
        it with my own eyes. In fact, I had not heard the half of your great wisdom!
        It is far beyond what I was told. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'How happy your people must be! What a privilege for your officials
        to stand here day after day, listening to your wisdom! '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Praise the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God, who delights in
        you and has placed you on the throne as king to rule for him. Because God
        loves Israel and desires this kingdom to last forever, he has made you king
        over them so you can rule with justice and righteousness.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Then she gave the king a gift of 9,000 pounds[[COMMENT(0)]] of gold,
        great quantities of spices, and precious jewels. Never before had there been
        spices as fine as those the queen of Sheba gave to King Solomon.  '
      comments:
      - number: '9:9 '
        content: Hebrew <b>120 talents </b>[4,000 kilograms].
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: '(In addition, the crews of Hiram and Solomon brought gold from Ophir,
        and they also brought red sandalwood[[COMMENT(0)]] and precious jewels. '
      comments:
      - number: '9:10 '
        content: Hebrew <b>algum wood </b>(also in 9:11); perhaps a variant spelling
          of <b>almug. </b>Compare parallel text at 1 Kgs 10:11-12.
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'The king used the sandalwood to make steps[[COMMENT(0)]] for the
        Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and the royal palace, and to construct
        lyres and harps for the musicians. Never before had such beautiful things
        been seen in Judah.)  '
      comments:
      - number: '9:11 '
        content: Or <b>gateways. </b>The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - name: "12: Solomon\u2019s Wealth and Splendor"
      title: "Solomon\u2019s Wealth and Splendor"
      number: 12
      content: "King Solomon gave the queen of Sheba whatever she asked for\u2014gifts
        of greater value than the gifts she had given him. Then she and all her attendants
        returned to their own land.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Each year Solomon received about 25 tons[[COMMENT(0)]] of gold. '
      comments:
      - number: '9:13 '
        content: Hebrew <b>666 talents </b>[23 metric tons].
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'This did not include the additional revenue he received from merchants
        and traders. All the kings of Arabia and the governors of the provinces also
        brought gold and silver to Solomon.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'King Solomon made 200 large shields of hammered gold, each weighing
        more than 15 pounds.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '9:15 '
        content: Hebrew <b>600 [shekels] of hammered gold </b>[6.8 kilograms].
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'He also made 300 smaller shields of hammered gold, each weighing
        more than 7-1/2 pounds.[[COMMENT(0)]] The king placed these shields in the
        Palace of the Forest of Lebanon.  '
      comments:
      - number: '9:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>300 [shekels] of gold </b>[3.4 kilograms].
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Then the king made a huge throne, decorated with ivory and overlaid
        with pure gold. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'The throne had six steps, with a footstool of gold. There were armrests
        on both sides of the seat, and the figure of a lion stood on each side of
        the throne. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'There were also twelve other lions, one standing on each end of the
        six steps. No other throne in all the world could be compared with it!  '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "All of King Solomon\u2019s drinking cups were solid gold, as were
        all the utensils in the Palace of the Forest of Lebanon. They were not made
        of silver, for silver was considered worthless in Solomon\u2019s day!  "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'The king had a fleet of trading ships of Tarshish manned by the sailors
        sent by Hiram.[[COMMENT(0)]] Once every three years the ships returned, loaded
        with gold, silver, ivory, apes, and peacocks.[[COMMENT(1)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '9:21a '
        content: Hebrew <b>Huram, </b>a variant spelling of Hiram.
      - number: '9:21b '
        content: Or <b>and baboons.</b>
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'So King Solomon became richer and wiser than any other king on earth. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'Kings from every nation came to consult him and to hear the wisdom
        God had given him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'Year after year everyone who visited brought him gifts of silver
        and gold, clothing, weapons, spices, horses, and mules.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'Solomon had 4,000 stalls for his horses and chariots, and he had
        12,000 horses.[[COMMENT(0)]] He stationed some of them in the chariot cities,
        and some near him in Jerusalem. '
      comments:
      - number: '9:25 '
        content: Or <b>12,000 charioteers.</b>
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'He ruled over all the kings from the Euphrates River[[COMMENT(0)]]
        in the north to the land of the Philistines and the border of Egypt in the
        south. '
      comments:
      - number: '9:26 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the river.</b>
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'The king made silver as plentiful in Jerusalem as stone. And valuable
        cedar timber was as common as the sycamore-fig trees that grow in the foothills
        of Judah.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '9:27 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Shephelah.</b>
    - name: "28: Summary of Solomon\u2019s Reign"
      title: "Summary of Solomon\u2019s Reign"
      number: 28
      content: "Solomon\u2019s horses were imported from Egypt[[COMMENT(0)]] and
        many other countries.  "
      comments:
      - number: '9:28 '
        content: Possibly <b>Muzur, </b>a district near Cilicia.
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "The rest of the events of Solomon\u2019s reign, from beginning to
        end, are recorded in The Record of Nathan the Prophet, and The Prophecy of
        Ahijah from Shiloh, and also in The Visions of Iddo the Seer, concerning
        Jeroboam son of Nebat. "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'Solomon ruled in Jerusalem over all Israel for forty years. '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: When he died, he was buried in the City of David, named for his father.
        Then his son Rehoboam became the next king.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Northern Tribes Revolt'
      title: The Northern Tribes Revolt
      number: 1
      content: '  Rehoboam went to Shechem, where all Israel had gathered to make
        him king. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'When Jeroboam son of Nebat heard of this, he returned from Egypt,
        for he had fled to Egypt to escape from King Solomon. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'The leaders of Israel summoned him, and Jeroboam and all Israel went
        to speak with Rehoboam. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "\u201CYour father was a hard master,\u201D they said. \u201CLighten
        the harsh labor demands and heavy taxes that your father imposed on us. Then
        we will be your loyal subjects.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Rehoboam replied, \u201CCome back in three days for my answer.\u201D
        So the people went away.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Then King Rehoboam discussed the matter with the older men who had
        counseled his father, Solomon. \u201CWhat is your advice?\u201D he asked.
        \u201CHow should I answer these people?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "The older counselors replied, \u201CIf you are good to these people
        and do your best to please them and give them a favorable answer, they will
        always be your loyal subjects.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'But Rehoboam rejected the advice of the older men and instead asked
        the opinion of the young men who had grown up with him and were now his advisers. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CWhat is your advice?\u201D he asked them. \u201CHow should
        I answer these people who want me to lighten the burdens imposed by my father?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "The young men replied, \u201CThis is what you should tell those complainers
        who want a lighter burden: \u2018My little finger is thicker than my father\u2019s
        waist! "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Yes, my father laid heavy burdens on you, but I\u2019m going to make
        them even heavier! My father beat you with whips, but I will beat you with
        scorpions!\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Three days later Jeroboam and all the people returned to hear Rehoboam\u2019s
        decision, just as the king had ordered. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'But Rehoboam spoke harshly to them, for he rejected the advice of
        the older counselors '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "and followed the counsel of his younger advisers. He told the people,
        \u201CMy father laid[[COMMENT(0)]] heavy burdens on you, but I\u2019m going
        to make them even heavier! My father beat you with whips, but I will beat
        you with scorpions!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '10:14 '
        content: As in Greek version and many Hebrew manuscripts (see also 1 Kgs
          12:14); Masoretic Text reads <b>I will lay.</b>
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "So the king paid no attention to the people. This turn of events
        was the will of God, for it fulfilled the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        message to Jeroboam son of Nebat through the prophet Ahijah from Shiloh.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "When all Israel realized[[COMMENT(0)]] that the king had refused
        to listen to them, they responded,\u201CDown with the dynasty of David!We
        have no interest in the son of Jesse.Back to your homes, O Israel!Look out
        for your own house, O David!\u201DSo all the people of Israel returned home. "
      comments:
      - number: '10:16 '
        content: As in Syriac version, Latin Vulgate, and many Hebrew manuscripts
          (see also 1 Kgs 12:16); Masoretic Text lacks <b>realized.</b>
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'But Rehoboam continued to rule over the Israelites who lived in the
        towns of Judah.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'King Rehoboam sent Adoniram,[[COMMENT(0)]] who was in charge of forced
        labor, to restore order, but the people of Israel stoned him to death. When
        this news reached King Rehoboam, he quickly jumped into his chariot and fled
        to Jerusalem. '
      comments:
      - number: '10:18 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Hadoram, </b>a variant spelling of Adoniram; compare 1
          Kgs 4:6; 5:14; 12:18.
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: And to this day the northern tribes of Israel have refused to be ruled
        by a descendant of David.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Shemaiah\u2019s Prophecy"
      title: "Shemaiah\u2019s Prophecy"
      number: 1
      content: "  When Rehoboam arrived at Jerusalem, he mobilized the men of Judah
        and Benjamin\u2014180,000 select troops\u2014to fight against Israel and
        to restore the kingdom to himself.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Shemaiah, the man of
        God, '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "\u201CSay to Rehoboam son of Solomon, king of Judah, and to all the
        Israelites in Judah and Benjamin: "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: Rehoboam Fortifies Judah'
      title: Rehoboam Fortifies Judah
      number: 4
      content: "\u2018This is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: Do not fight
        against your relatives. Go back home, for what has happened is my doing!\u2019\u201D
        So they obeyed the message of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and did not
        fight against Jeroboam.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Rehoboam remained in Jerusalem and fortified various towns for the
        defense of Judah. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'He built up Bethlehem, Etam, Tekoa, '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Beth-zur, Soco, Adullam, '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Gath, Mareshah, Ziph, '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Adoraim, Lachish, Azekah, '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Zorah, Aijalon, and Hebron. These became the fortified towns of Judah
        and Benjamin. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Rehoboam strengthened their defenses and stationed commanders in
        them, and he stored supplies of food, olive oil, and wine. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'He also put shields and spears in these towns as a further safety
        measure. So only Judah and Benjamin remained under his control.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'But all the priests and Levites living among the northern tribes
        of Israel sided with Rehoboam. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'The Levites even abandoned their pasturelands and property and moved
        to Judah and Jerusalem, because Jeroboam and his sons would not allow them
        to serve the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> as priests. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Jeroboam appointed his own priests to serve at the pagan shrines,
        where they worshiped the goat and calf idols he had made. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'From all the tribes of Israel, those who sincerely wanted to worship
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel, followed the Levites
        to Jerusalem, where they could offer sacrifices to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of their ancestors. '
      comments: []
    - name: "17: Rehoboam\u2019s Family"
      title: "Rehoboam\u2019s Family"
      number: 17
      content: 'This strengthened the kingdom of Judah, and for three years they
        supported Rehoboam son of Solomon, for during those years they faithfully
        followed in the footsteps of David and Solomon.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Rehoboam married his cousin Mahalath, the daughter of David\u2019s
        son Jerimoth and of Abihail, the daughter of Eliab son of Jesse. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Mahalath had three sons\u2014Jeush, Shemariah, and Zaham.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Later Rehoboam married another cousin, Maacah, the granddaughter
        of Absalom. Maacah gave birth to Abijah, Attai, Ziza, and Shelomith. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'Rehoboam loved Maacah more than any of his other wives and concubines.
        In all, he had eighteen wives and sixty concubines, and they gave birth to
        twenty-eight sons and sixty daughters.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Rehoboam appointed Maacah\u2019s son Abijah as leader among the princes,
        making it clear that he would be the next king. "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: Rehoboam also wisely gave responsibilities to his other sons and stationed
        some of them in the fortified towns throughout the land of Judah and Benjamin.
        He provided them with generous provisions, and he found many wives for them.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Egypt Invades Judah'
      title: Egypt Invades Judah
      number: 1
      content: '  But when Rehoboam was firmly established and strong, he abandoned
        the Law of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, and all Israel followed him in
        this sin. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Because they were unfaithful to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        King Shishak of Egypt came up and attacked Jerusalem in the fifth year of
        King Rehoboam\u2019s reign. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'He came with 1,200 chariots, 60,000 horses,[[COMMENT(0)]] and a countless
        army of foot soldiers, including Libyans, Sukkites, and Ethiopians.[[COMMENT(1)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '12:3a '
        content: Or <b>charioteers, </b>or <b>horsemen.</b>
      - number: '12:3b '
        content: Hebrew <b>and Cushites.</b>
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Shishak conquered Judah\u2019s fortified towns and then advanced
        to attack Jerusalem.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "The prophet Shemaiah then met with Rehoboam and Judah\u2019s leaders,
        who had all fled to Jerusalem because of Shishak. Shemaiah told them, \u201CThis
        is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: You have abandoned me, so I
        am abandoning you to Shishak.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Then the leaders of Israel and the king humbled themselves and said,
        \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is right in doing this to us!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "When the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> saw their change of heart, he
        gave this message to Shemaiah: \u201CSince the people have humbled themselves,
        I will not completely destroy them and will soon give them some relief. I
        will not use Shishak to pour out my anger on Jerusalem. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "But they will become his subjects, so they will know the difference
        between serving me and serving earthly rulers.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "So King Shishak of Egypt came up and attacked Jerusalem. He ransacked
        the treasuries of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple and the royal
        palace; he stole everything, including all the gold shields Solomon had made. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'King Rehoboam later replaced them with bronze shields as substitutes,
        and he entrusted them to the care of the commanders of the guard who protected
        the entrance to the royal palace. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Whenever the king went to the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the guards would also take the shields and then return them to the guardroom. '
      comments: []
    - name: "12: Summary of Rehoboam\u2019s Reign"
      title: "Summary of Rehoboam\u2019s Reign"
      number: 12
      content: "Because Rehoboam humbled himself, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        anger was turned away, and he did not destroy him completely. There were
        still some good things in the land of Judah.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "King Rehoboam firmly established himself in Jerusalem and continued
        to rule. He was forty-one years old when he became king, and he reigned seventeen
        years in Jerusalem, the city the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had chosen from
        among all the tribes of Israel as the place to honor his name. Rehoboam\u2019s
        mother was Naamah, a woman from Ammon. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'But he was an evil king, for he did not seek the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        with all his heart.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "The rest of the events of Rehoboam\u2019s reign, from beginning to
        end, are recorded in The Record of Shemaiah the Prophet and The Record of
        Iddo the Seer, which are part of the genealogical record. Rehoboam and Jeroboam
        were continually at war with each other. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: When Rehoboam died, he was buried in the City of David. Then his son
        Abijah became the next king.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Abijah\u2019s War with Jeroboam"
      title: "Abijah\u2019s War with Jeroboam"
      number: 1
      content: "  Abijah began to rule over Judah in the eighteenth year of Jeroboam\u2019s
        reign in Israel. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'He reigned in Jerusalem three years. His mother was Maacah,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        the daughter of Uriel from Gibeah.Then war broke out between Abijah and Jeroboam. '
      comments:
      - number: '13:2 '
        content: As in most Greek manuscripts and Syriac version (see also 2 Chr
          11:20-21; 1 Kgs 15:2); Hebrew reads <b>Micaiah, </b>a variant spelling
          of Maacah.
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Judah, led by King Abijah, fielded 400,000 select warriors, while
        Jeroboam mustered 800,000 select troops from Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "When the army of Judah arrived in the hill country of Ephraim, Abijah
        stood on Mount Zemaraim and shouted to Jeroboam and all Israel: \u201CListen
        to me! "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Don\u2019t you realize that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the
        God of Israel, made a lasting covenant[[COMMENT(0)]] with David, giving him
        and his descendants the throne of Israel forever? "
      comments:
      - number: '13:5 '
        content: Hebrew <b>a covenant of salt.</b>
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Yet Jeroboam son of Nebat, a mere servant of David\u2019s son Solomon,
        rebelled against his master. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Then a whole gang of scoundrels joined him, defying Solomon\u2019s
        son Rehoboam when he was young and inexperienced and could not stand up to
        them.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201CDo you really think you can stand against the kingdom of the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> that is led by the descendants of David? You
        may have a vast army, and you have those gold calves that Jeroboam made as
        your gods. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'But you have chased away the priests of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        (the descendants of Aaron) and the Levites, and you have appointed your own
        priests, just like the pagan nations. You let anyone become a priest these
        days! Whoever comes to be dedicated with a young bull and seven rams can
        become a priest of these so-called gods of yours!  '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201CBut as for us, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is our God,
        and we have not abandoned him. Only the descendants of Aaron serve the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        as priests, and the Levites alone may help them in their work. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'They present burnt offerings and fragrant incense to the <smallcaps>Lord
        </smallcaps>every morning and evening. They place the Bread of the Presence
        on the holy table, and they light the gold lampstand every evening. We are
        following the instructions of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> our God, but
        you have abandoned him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "So you see, God is with us. He is our leader. His priests blow their
        trumpets and lead us into battle against you. O people of Israel, do not
        fight against the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of your ancestors,
        for you will not succeed!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Meanwhile, Jeroboam had secretly sent part of his army around behind
        the men of Judah to ambush them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'When Judah realized that they were being attacked from the front
        and the rear, they cried out to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> for help.
        Then the priests blew the trumpets, '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'and the men of Judah began to shout. At the sound of their battle
        cry, God defeated Jeroboam and all Israel and routed them before Abijah and
        the army of Judah.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'The Israelite army fled from Judah, and God handed them over to Judah
        in defeat. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Abijah and his army inflicted heavy losses on them; 500,000 of Israel\u2019s
        select troops were killed that day. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'So Judah defeated Israel on that occasion because they trusted in
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of their ancestors. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Abijah and his army pursued Jeroboam\u2019s troops and captured some
        of his towns, including Bethel, Jeshanah, and Ephron, along with their surrounding
        villages.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "So Jeroboam of Israel never regained his power during Abijah\u2019s
        lifetime, and finally the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> struck him down and
        he died. "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'Meanwhile, Abijah of Judah grew more and more powerful. He married
        fourteen wives and had twenty-two sons and sixteen daughters.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "The rest of the events of Abijah\u2019s reign, including his words
        and deeds, are recorded in The Commentary of Iddo the Prophet."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Early Years of Asa\u2019s Reign"
      title: "Early Years of Asa\u2019s Reign"
      number: 1
      content: '    [[COMMENT(0)]]When Abijah died, he was buried in the City of
        David. Then his son Asa became the next king. There was peace in the land
        for ten years. '
      comments:
      - number: '14:1 '
        content: '  Verse 14:1 is numbered 13:23 in Hebrew text.  '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: '[[COMMENT(0)]]Asa did what was pleasing and good in the sight of
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> his God. '
      comments:
      - number: '14:2 '
        content: Verses 14:2-15 are numbered 14:1-14 in Hebrew text.
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'He removed the foreign altars and the pagan shrines. He smashed the
        sacred pillars and cut down the Asherah poles. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'He commanded the people of Judah to seek the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of their ancestors, and to obey his law and his commands. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Asa also removed the pagan shrines, as well as the incense altars
        from every one of Judah\u2019s towns. So Asa\u2019s kingdom enjoyed a period
        of peace. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'During those peaceful years, he was able to build up the fortified
        towns throughout Judah. No one tried to make war against him at this time,
        for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was giving him rest from his enemies.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Asa told the people of Judah, \u201CLet us build towns and fortify
        them with walls, towers, gates, and bars. The land is still ours because
        we sought the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> our God, and he has given us peace
        on every side.\u201D So they went ahead with these projects and brought them
        to completion.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'King Asa had an army of 300,000 warriors from the tribe of Judah,
        armed with large shields and spears. He also had an army of 280,000 warriors
        from the tribe of Benjamin, armed with small shields and bows. Both armies
        were composed of well-trained fighting men.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Once an Ethiopian[[COMMENT(0)]] named Zerah attacked Judah with an
        army of 1,000,000 men[[COMMENT(1)]] and 300 chariots. They advanced to the
        town of Mareshah, '
      comments:
      - number: '14:9a '
        content: Hebrew <b>a Cushite.</b>
      - number: '14:9b '
        content: Or <b>an army of thousands and thousands; </b>Hebrew reads <b>an
          army of a thousand thousands.</b>
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'so Asa deployed his armies for battle in the valley north of Mareshah.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '14:10 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>valley of Zephathah near Mareshah.</b>
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Then Asa cried out to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> his God, \u201CO
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, no one but you can help the powerless against
        the mighty! Help us, O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> our God, for we trust
        in you alone. It is in your name that we have come against this vast horde.
        O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, you are our God; do not let mere men prevail
        against you!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> defeated the Ethiopians[[COMMENT(0)]]
        in the presence of Asa and the army of Judah, and the enemy fled. '
      comments:
      - number: '14:12 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Cushites; </b>also in 14:13.
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Asa and his army pursued them as far as Gerar, and so many Ethiopians
        fell that they were unable to rally. They were destroyed by the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and his army, and the army of Judah carried off a vast amount of plunder.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'While they were at Gerar, they attacked all the towns in that area,
        and terror from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> came upon the people there.
        As a result, a vast amount of plunder was taken from these towns, too. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: They also attacked the camps of herdsmen and captured many sheep,
        goats, and camels before finally returning to Jerusalem.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Asa\u2019s Religious Reforms"
      title: "Asa\u2019s Religious Reforms"
      number: 1
      content: '  Then the Spirit of God came upon Azariah son of Oded, '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "and he went out to meet King Asa as he was returning from the battle.
        \u201CListen to me, Asa!\u201D he shouted. \u201CListen, all you people of
        Judah and Benjamin! The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will stay with you as
        long as you stay with him! Whenever you seek him, you will find him. But
        if you abandon him, he will abandon you. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'For a long time Israel was without the true God, without a priest
        to teach them, and without the Law to instruct them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'But whenever they were in trouble and turned to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel, and sought him out, they found him.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "\u201CDuring those dark times, it was not safe to travel. Problems
        troubled the people of every land. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Nation fought against nation, and city against city, for God was
        troubling them with every kind of problem. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "But as for you, be strong and courageous, for your work will be rewarded.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "When Asa heard this message from Azariah the prophet,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        he took courage and removed all the detestable idols from the land of Judah
        and Benjamin and in the towns he had captured in the hill country of Ephraim.
        And he repaired the altar of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, which stood
        in front of the entry room of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple.  "
      comments:
      - number: '15:8 '
        content: As in Syriac version and Latin Vulgate (see also 15:1); Hebrew reads
          <b>from Oded the prophet.</b>
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Then Asa called together all the people of Judah and Benjamin, along
        with the people of Ephraim, Manasseh, and Simeon who had settled among them.
        For many from Israel had moved to Judah during Asa\u2019s reign when they
        saw that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> his God was with him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "The people gathered at Jerusalem in late spring,[[COMMENT(0)]] during
        the fifteenth year of Asa\u2019s reign.  "
      comments:
      - number: '15:10 '
        content: Hebrew <b>in the third month. </b>This month of the ancient Hebrew
          lunar calendar usually occurs within the months of May and June.
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'On that day they sacrificed to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> 700
        cattle and 7,000 sheep and goats from the plunder they had taken in the battle. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'Then they entered into a covenant to seek the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of their ancestors, with all their heart and soul. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "They agreed that anyone who refused to seek the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel, would be put to death\u2014whether young or old, man or
        woman. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "They shouted out their oath of loyalty to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        with trumpets blaring and rams\u2019 horns sounding. "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'All in Judah were happy about this covenant, for they had entered
        into it with all their heart. They earnestly sought after God, and they found
        him. And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> gave them rest from their enemies
        on every side.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'King Asa even deposed his grandmother[[COMMENT(0)]] Maacah from her
        position as queen mother because she had made an obscene Asherah pole. He
        cut down her obscene pole, broke it up, and burned it in the Kidron Valley. '
      comments:
      - number: '15:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>his mother.</b>
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Although the pagan shrines were not removed from Israel, Asa\u2019s
        heart remained completely faithful throughout his life. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'He brought into the Temple of God the silver and gold and the various
        items that he and his father had dedicated.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "So there was no more war until the thirty-fifth year of Asa\u2019s
        reign."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Final Years of Asa\u2019s Reign"
      title: "Final Years of Asa\u2019s Reign"
      number: 1
      content: "  In the thirty-sixth year of Asa\u2019s reign, King Baasha of Israel
        invaded Judah and fortified Ramah in order to prevent anyone from entering
        or leaving King Asa\u2019s territory in Judah.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Asa responded by removing the silver and gold from the treasuries
        of the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and the royal palace. He
        sent it to King Ben-hadad of Aram, who was ruling in Damascus, along with
        this message:  '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "\u201CLet there be a treaty[[COMMENT(0)]] between you and me like
        the one between your father and my father. See, I am sending you silver and
        gold. Break your treaty with King Baasha of Israel so that he will leave
        me alone.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '16:3 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>There is a treaty.</b>
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Ben-hadad agreed to King Asa\u2019s request and sent the commanders
        of his army to attack the towns of Israel. They conquered the towns of Ijon,
        Dan, Abel-beth-maacah,[[COMMENT(0)]] and all the store cities in Naphtali. "
      comments:
      - number: '16:4 '
        content: As in parallel text at 1 Kgs 15:20; Hebrew reads <b>Abel-maim, </b>another
          name for Abel-beth-maacah.
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'As soon as Baasha of Israel heard what was happening, he abandoned
        his project of fortifying Ramah and stopped all work on it. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Then King Asa called out all the men of Judah to carry away the building
        stones and timbers that Baasha had been using to fortify Ramah. Asa used
        these materials to fortify the towns of Geba and Mizpah.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "At that time Hanani the seer came to King Asa and told him, \u201CBecause
        you have put your trust in the king of Aram instead of in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God, you missed your chance to destroy the army of the king of Aram. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Don\u2019t you remember what happened to the Ethiopians[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and Libyans and their vast army, with all of their chariots and charioteers?[[COMMENT(1)]]
        At that time you relied on the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, and he handed
        them over to you. "
      comments:
      - number: '16:8a '
        content: Hebrew <b>Cushites.</b>
      - number: '16:8b '
        content: Or <b>and horsemen?</b>
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "The eyes of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> search the whole earth
        in order to strengthen those whose hearts are fully committed to him. What
        a fool you have been! From now on you will be at war.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: "10: Summary of Asa\u2019s Reign"
      title: "Summary of Asa\u2019s Reign"
      number: 10
      content: 'Asa became so angry with Hanani for saying this that he threw him
        into prison and put him in stocks. At that time Asa also began to oppress
        some of his people.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "The rest of the events of Asa\u2019s reign, from beginning to end,
        are recorded in The Book of the Kings of Judah and Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "In the thirty-ninth year of his reign, Asa developed a serious foot
        disease. Yet even with the severity of his disease, he did not seek the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        help but turned only to his physicians. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'So he died in the forty-first year of his reign. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: He was buried in the tomb he had carved out for himself in the City
        of David. He was laid on a bed perfumed with sweet spices and fragrant ointments,
        and the people built a huge funeral fire in his honor.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Jehoshaphat Rules in Judah'
      title: Jehoshaphat Rules in Judah
      number: 1
      content: "  Then Jehoshaphat, Asa\u2019s son, became the next king. He strengthened
        Judah to stand against any attack from Israel. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'He stationed troops in all the fortified towns of Judah, and he assigned
        additional garrisons to the land of Judah and to the towns of Ephraim that
        his father, Asa, had captured.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was with Jehoshaphat because he followed
        the example of his father\u2019s early years[[COMMENT(0)]] and did not worship
        the images of Baal. "
      comments:
      - number: '17:3 '
        content: Some Hebrew manuscripts read <b>the example of his father, David.</b>
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "He sought his father\u2019s God and obeyed his commands instead of
        following the evil practices of the kingdom of Israel. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> established Jehoshaphat\u2019s
        control over the kingdom of Judah. All the people of Judah brought gifts
        to Jehoshaphat, so he became very wealthy and highly esteemed. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'He was deeply committed to[[COMMENT(0)]] the ways of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        He removed the pagan shrines and Asherah poles from Judah.  '
      comments:
      - number: '17:6 '
        content: Hebrew <b>His heart was courageous in.</b>
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'In the third year of his reign Jehoshaphat sent his officials to
        teach in all the towns of Judah. These officials included Ben-hail, Obadiah,
        Zechariah, Nethanel, and Micaiah. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'He sent Levites along with them, including Shemaiah, Nethaniah, Zebadiah,
        Asahel, Shemiramoth, Jehonathan, Adonijah, Tobijah, and Tob-adonijah. He
        also sent out the priests Elishama and Jehoram. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'They took copies of the Book of the Law of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and traveled around through all the towns of Judah, teaching the people.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Then the fear of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> fell over all the
        surrounding kingdoms so that none of them wanted to declare war on Jehoshaphat. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Some of the Philistines brought him gifts and silver as tribute,
        and the Arabs brought 7,700 rams and 7,700 male goats.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'So Jehoshaphat became more and more powerful and built fortresses
        and storage cities throughout Judah. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "He stored numerous supplies in Judah\u2019s towns and stationed an
        army of seasoned troops at Jerusalem. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'His army was enrolled according to ancestral clans.From Judah there
        were 300,000 troops organized in units of 1,000, under the command of Adnah. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Next in command was Jehohanan, who commanded 280,000 troops. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Next was Amasiah son of Zicri, who volunteered for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        service, with 200,000 troops under his command.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'From Benjamin there were 200,000 troops equipped with bows and shields.
        They were under the command of Eliada, a veteran soldier. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Next in command was Jehozabad, who commanded 180,000 armed men.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: These were the troops stationed in Jerusalem to serve the king, besides
        those Jehoshaphat stationed in the fortified towns throughout Judah.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Jehoshaphat and Ahab'
      title: Jehoshaphat and Ahab
      number: 1
      content: "  Jehoshaphat enjoyed great riches and high esteem, and he made an
        alliance with Ahab of Israel by having his son marry Ahab\u2019s daughter. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'A few years later he went to Samaria to visit Ahab, who prepared
        a great banquet for him and his officials. They butchered great numbers of
        sheep, goats, and cattle for the feast. Then Ahab enticed Jehoshaphat to
        join forces with him to recover Ramoth-gilead.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "\u201CWill you go with me to Ramoth-gilead?\u201D King Ahab of Israel
        asked King Jehoshaphat of Judah.Jehoshaphat replied, \u201CWhy, of course!
        You and I are as one, and my troops are your troops. We will certainly join
        you in battle.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Then Jehoshaphat added, \u201CBut first let\u2019s find out what
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "So the king of Israel summoned the prophets, 400 of them, and asked
        them, \u201CShould we go to war against Ramoth-gilead, or should I hold back?\u201DThey
        all replied, \u201CYes, go right ahead! God will give the king victory.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "But Jehoshaphat asked, \u201CIs there not also a prophet of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        here? We should ask him the same question.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "The king of Israel replied to Jehoshaphat, \u201CThere is one more
        man who could consult the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> for us, but I hate
        him. He never prophesies anything but trouble for me! His name is Micaiah
        son of Imlah.\u201DJehoshaphat replied, \u201CThat\u2019s not the way a king
        should talk! Let\u2019s hear what he has to say.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: Micaiah Prophesies against Ahab'
      title: Micaiah Prophesies against Ahab
      number: 8
      content: "So the king of Israel called one of his officials and said, \u201CQuick!
        Bring Micaiah son of Imlah.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "King Ahab of Israel and King Jehoshaphat of Judah, dressed in their
        royal robes, were sitting on thrones at the threshing floor near the gate
        of Samaria. All of Ahab\u2019s prophets were prophesying there in front of
        them. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "One of them, Zedekiah son of Kenaanah, made some iron horns and proclaimed,
        \u201CThis is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: With these horns
        you will gore the Arameans to death!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "All the other prophets agreed. \u201CYes,\u201D they said, \u201Cgo
        up to Ramoth-gilead and be victorious, for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        will give the king victory!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Meanwhile, the messenger who went to get Micaiah said to him, \u201CLook,
        all the prophets are promising victory for the king. Be sure that you agree
        with them and promise success.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "But Micaiah replied, \u201CAs surely as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        lives, I will say only what my God says.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "When Micaiah arrived before the king, Ahab asked him, \u201CMicaiah,
        should we go to war against Ramoth-gilead, or should I hold back?\u201DMicaiah
        replied sarcastically, \u201CYes, go up and be victorious, for you will have
        victory over them!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "But the king replied sharply, \u201CHow many times must I demand
        that you speak only the truth to me when you speak for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Then Micaiah told him, \u201CIn a vision I saw all Israel scattered
        on the mountains, like sheep without a shepherd. And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        said, \u2018Their master has been killed.[[COMMENT(0)]] Send them home in
        peace.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '18:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>These people have no master.</b>
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "\u201CDidn\u2019t I tell you?\u201D the king of Israel exclaimed
        to Jehoshaphat. \u201CHe never prophesies anything but trouble for me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Then Micaiah continued, \u201CListen to what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says! I saw the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> sitting on his throne with all
        the armies of heaven around him, on his right and on his left. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said, \u2018Who can entice King
        Ahab of Israel to go into battle against Ramoth-gilead so he can be killed?\u2019\u201CThere
        were many suggestions, "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "and finally a spirit approached the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and
        said, \u2018I can do it!\u2019\u201C\u2018How will you do this?\u2019 the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> asked.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "\u201CAnd the spirit replied, \u2018I will go out and inspire all
        of Ahab\u2019s prophets to speak lies.\u2019\u201C\u2018You will succeed,\u2019
        said the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. \u2018Go ahead and do it.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "\u201CSo you see, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has put a lying
        spirit in the mouths of your prophets. For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has pronounced your doom.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Then Zedekiah son of Kenaanah walked up to Micaiah and slapped him
        across the face. \u201CSince when did the Spirit of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        leave me to speak to you?\u201D he demanded.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "And Micaiah replied, \u201CYou will find out soon enough when you
        are trying to hide in some secret room!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "\u201CArrest him!\u201D the king of Israel ordered. \u201CTake him
        back to Amon, the governor of the city, and to my son Joash. "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "Give them this order from the king: \u2018Put this man in prison,
        and feed him nothing but bread and water until I return safely from the battle!\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: The Death of Ahab'
      title: The Death of Ahab
      number: 27
      content: "But Micaiah replied, \u201CIf you return safely, it will mean that
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has not spoken through me!\u201D Then he
        added to those standing around, \u201CEveryone mark my words!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'So King Ahab of Israel and King Jehoshaphat of Judah led their armies
        against Ramoth-gilead. '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "The king of Israel said to Jehoshaphat, \u201CAs we go into battle,
        I will disguise myself so no one will recognize me, but you wear your royal
        robes.\u201D So the king of Israel disguised himself, and they went into
        battle.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "Meanwhile, the king of Aram had issued these orders to his chariot
        commanders: \u201CAttack only the king of Israel! Don\u2019t bother with
        anyone else.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "So when the Aramean chariot commanders saw Jehoshaphat in his royal
        robes, they went after him. \u201CThere is the king of Israel!\u201D they
        shouted. But Jehoshaphat called out, and the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        saved him. God helped him by turning the attackers away from him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'As soon as the chariot commanders realized he was not the king of
        Israel, they stopped chasing him.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "An Aramean soldier, however, randomly shot an arrow at the Israelite
        troops and hit the king of Israel between the joints of his armor. \u201CTurn
        the horses[[COMMENT(0)]] and get me out of here!\u201D Ahab groaned to the
        driver of the chariot. \u201CI\u2019m badly wounded!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '18:33 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Turn your hand.</b>
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: The battle raged all that day, and the king of Israel propped himself
        up in his chariot facing the Arameans. In the evening, just as the sun was
        setting, he died.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Jehoshaphat Appoints Judges'
      title: Jehoshaphat Appoints Judges
      number: 1
      content: '  When King Jehoshaphat of Judah arrived safely home in Jerusalem, '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Jehu son of Hanani the seer went out to meet him. \u201CWhy should
        you help the wicked and love those who hate the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>?\u201D
        he asked the king. \u201CBecause of what you have done, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        is very angry with you. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Even so, there is some good in you, for you have removed the Asherah
        poles throughout the land, and you have committed yourself to seeking God.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'Jehoshaphat lived in Jerusalem, but he went out among the people,
        traveling from Beersheba to the hill country of Ephraim, encouraging the
        people to return to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of their ancestors. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'He appointed judges throughout the nation in all the fortified towns, '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "and he said to them, \u201CAlways think carefully before pronouncing
        judgment. Remember that you do not judge to please people but to please the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. He will be with you when you render the verdict
        in each case. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Fear the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and judge with integrity, for
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> our God does not tolerate perverted justice,
        partiality, or the taking of bribes.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "In Jerusalem, Jehoshaphat appointed some of the Levites and priests
        and clan leaders in Israel to serve as judges[[COMMENT(0)]] for cases involving
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s regulations and for civil disputes. "
      comments:
      - number: '19:8 '
        content: As in Greek version; the meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "These were his instructions to them: \u201CYou must always act in
        the fear of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, with faithfulness and an undivided
        heart. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Whenever a case comes to you from fellow citizens in an outlying
        town, whether a murder case or some other violation of God\u2019s laws, commands,
        decrees, or regulations, you must warn them not to sin against the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        so that he will not be angry with you and them. Do this and you will not
        be guilty.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "\u201CAmariah the high priest will have final say in all cases involving
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. Zebadiah son of Ishmael, a leader from the
        tribe of Judah, will have final say in all civil cases. The Levites will
        assist you in making sure that justice is served. Take courage as you fulfill
        your duties, and may the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> be with those who do
        what is right.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: War with Surrounding Nations'
      title: War with Surrounding Nations
      number: 1
      content: '  After this, the armies of the Moabites, Ammonites, and some of
        the Meunites[[COMMENT(0)]] declared war on Jehoshaphat. '
      comments:
      - number: '20:1 '
        content: As in some Greek manuscripts (see also 26:7); Hebrew repeats <b>Ammonites.</b>
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Messengers came and told Jehoshaphat, \u201CA vast army from Edom[[COMMENT(0)]]
        is marching against you from beyond the Dead Sea.[[COMMENT(1)]] They are
        already at Hazazon-tamar.\u201D (This was another name for En-gedi.)  "
      comments:
      - number: '20:2a '
        content: As in one Hebrew manuscript; most Hebrew manuscripts and ancient
          versions read <b>Aram.</b>
      - number: '20:2b '
        content: Hebrew <b>the sea.</b>
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Jehoshaphat was terrified by this news and begged the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        for guidance. He also ordered everyone in Judah to begin fasting. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "So people from all the towns of Judah came to Jerusalem to seek the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s help.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Jehoshaphat stood before the community of Judah and Jerusalem in
        front of the new courtyard at the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "He prayed, \u201CO <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, God of our ancestors,
        you alone are the God who is in heaven. You are ruler of all the kingdoms
        of the earth. You are powerful and mighty; no one can stand against you! "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'O our God, did you not drive out those who lived in this land when
        your people Israel arrived? And did you not give this land forever to the
        descendants of your friend Abraham? '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Your people settled here and built this Temple to honor your name. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "They said, \u2018Whenever we are faced with any calamity such as
        war,[[COMMENT(0)]] plague, or famine, we can come to stand in your presence
        before this Temple where your name is honored. We can cry out to you to save
        us, and you will hear us and rescue us.\u2019  "
      comments:
      - number: '20:9 '
        content: Or <b>sword of judgment; </b>or <b>sword, judgment.</b>
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201CAnd now see what the armies of Ammon, Moab, and Mount Seir
        are doing. You would not let our ancestors invade those nations when Israel
        left Egypt, so they went around them and did not destroy them. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Now see how they reward us! For they have come to throw us out of
        your land, which you gave us as an inheritance. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "O our God, won\u2019t you stop them? We are powerless against this
        mighty army that is about to attack us. We do not know what to do, but we
        are looking to you for help.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'As all the men of Judah stood before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        with their little ones, wives, and children, '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'the Spirit of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> came upon one of the
        men standing there. His name was Jahaziel son of Zechariah, son of Benaiah,
        son of Jeiel, son of Mattaniah, a Levite who was a descendant of Asaph.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "He said, \u201CListen, all you people of Judah and Jerusalem! Listen,
        King Jehoshaphat! This is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: Do not
        be afraid! Don\u2019t be discouraged by this mighty army, for the battle
        is not yours, but God\u2019s. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Tomorrow, march out against them. You will find them coming up through
        the ascent of Ziz at the end of the valley that opens into the wilderness
        of Jeruel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "But you will not even need to fight. Take your positions; then stand
        still and watch the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s victory. He is with
        you, O people of Judah and Jerusalem. Do not be afraid or discouraged. Go
        out against them tomorrow, for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is with you!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Then King Jehoshaphat bowed low with his face to the ground. And
        all the people of Judah and Jerusalem did the same, worshiping the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'Then the Levites from the clans of Kohath and Korah stood to praise
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel, with a very loud shout.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Early the next morning the army of Judah went out into the wilderness
        of Tekoa. On the way Jehoshaphat stopped and said, \u201CListen to me, all
        you people of Judah and Jerusalem! Believe in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God, and you will be able to stand firm. Believe in his prophets, and
        you will succeed.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "After consulting the people, the king appointed singers to walk ahead
        of the army, singing to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and praising him
        for his holy splendor. This is what they sang:\u201CGive thanks to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>;his
        faithful love endures forever!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'At the very moment they began to sing and give praise, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        caused the armies of Ammon, Moab, and Mount Seir to start fighting among
        themselves. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'The armies of Moab and Ammon turned against their allies from Mount
        Seir and killed every one of them. After they had destroyed the army of Seir,
        they began attacking each other. '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'So when the army of Judah arrived at the lookout point in the wilderness,
        all they saw were dead bodies lying on the ground as far as they could see.
        Not a single one of the enemy had escaped.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "King Jehoshaphat and his men went out to gather the plunder. They
        found vast amounts of equipment, clothing,[[COMMENT(0)]] and other valuables\u2014more
        than they could carry. There was so much plunder that it took them three
        days just to collect it all! "
      comments:
      - number: '20:25 '
        content: As in some Hebrew manuscripts and Latin Vulgate; most Hebrew manuscripts
          read <b>corpses.</b>
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'On the fourth day they gathered in the Valley of Blessing,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        which got its name that day because the people praised and thanked the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        there. It is still called the Valley of Blessing today.  '
      comments:
      - number: '20:26 '
        content: Hebrew <b>valley of Beracah.</b>
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'Then all the men returned to Jerusalem, with Jehoshaphat leading
        them, overjoyed that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had given them victory
        over their enemies. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'They marched into Jerusalem to the music of harps, lyres, and trumpets,
        and they proceeded to the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'When all the surrounding kingdoms heard that the <smallcaps>Lord
        </smallcaps>himself had fought against the enemies of Israel, the fear of
        God came over them. '
      comments: []
    - name: "30: Summary of Jehoshaphat\u2019s Reign"
      title: "Summary of Jehoshaphat\u2019s Reign"
      number: 30
      content: "So Jehoshaphat\u2019s kingdom was at peace, for his God had given
        him rest on every side.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'So Jehoshaphat ruled over the land of Judah. He was thirty-five years
        old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem twenty-five years. His
        mother was Azubah, the daughter of Shilhi.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "Jehoshaphat was a good king, following the ways of his father, Asa.
        He did what was pleasing in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s sight. "
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'During his reign, however, he failed to remove all the pagan shrines,
        and the people never fully committed themselves to follow the God of their
        ancestors.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "The rest of the events of Jehoshaphat\u2019s reign, from beginning
        to end, are recorded in The Record of Jehu Son of Hanani, which is included
        in The Book of the Kings of Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: 'Some time later King Jehoshaphat of Judah made an alliance with King
        Ahaziah of Israel, who was very wicked.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '20:35 '
        content: Or <b>who made him do what was wicked.</b>
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: 'Together they built a fleet of trading ships[[COMMENT(0)]] at the
        port of Ezion-geber. '
      comments:
      - number: '20:36 '
        content: Hebrew <b>fleet of ships that could go to Tarshish.</b>
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "Then Eliezer son of Dodavahu from Mareshah prophesied against Jehoshaphat.
        He said, \u201CBecause you have allied yourself with King Ahaziah, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        will destroy your work.\u201D So the ships met with disaster and never put
        out to sea.[[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: '20:37 '
        content: Hebrew <b>never set sail for Tarshish.</b>
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Jehoram Rules in Judah'
      title: Jehoram Rules in Judah
      number: 1
      content: '  When Jehoshaphat died, he was buried with his ancestors in the
        City of David. Then his son Jehoram became the next king.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Jehoram\u2019s brothers\u2014the other sons of Jehoshaphat\u2014were
        Azariah, Jehiel, Zechariah, Azariahu, Michael, and Shephatiah; all these
        were the sons of Jehoshaphat king of Judah.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '21:2 '
        content: Masoretic Text reads <b>of Israel; </b>also in 21:4. The author
          of Chronicles sees Judah as representative of the true Israel. (Some Hebrew
          manuscripts, Greek and Syriac versions, and Latin Vulgate read <b>of Judah.</b>)
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Their father had given each of them valuable gifts of silver, gold,
        and costly items, and also some of Judah\u2019s fortified towns. However,
        he designated Jehoram as the next king because he was the oldest. "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'But when Jehoram had become solidly established as king, he killed
        all his brothers and some of the other leaders of Judah.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Jehoram was thirty-two years old when he became king, and he reigned
        in Jerusalem eight years. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "But Jehoram followed the example of the kings of Israel and was as
        wicked as King Ahab, for he had married one of Ahab\u2019s daughters. So
        Jehoram did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s sight. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> did not want to destroy David\u2019s
        dynasty, for he had made a covenant with David and promised that his descendants
        would continue to rule, shining like a lamp forever.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "During Jehoram\u2019s reign, the Edomites revolted against Judah
        and crowned their own king. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'So Jehoram went out with his full army and all his chariots. The
        Edomites surrounded him and his chariot commanders, but he went out at night
        and attacked them[[COMMENT(0)]] under cover of darkness. '
      comments:
      - number: '21:9 '
        content: Or <b>he went out and escaped. </b>The meaning of the Hebrew is
          uncertain.
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Even so, Edom has been independent from Judah to this day. The town
        of Libnah also revolted about that same time. All this happened because Jehoram
        had abandoned the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of his ancestors. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'He had built pagan shrines in the hill country of Judah and had led
        the people of Jerusalem and Judah to give themselves to pagan gods and to
        go astray.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Then Elijah the prophet wrote Jehoram this letter:\u201CThis is what
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of your ancestor David, says: You
        have not followed the good example of your father, Jehoshaphat, or your grandfather
        King Asa of Judah. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Instead, you have been as evil as the kings of Israel. You have led
        the people of Jerusalem and Judah to worship idols, just as King Ahab did
        in Israel. And you have even killed your own brothers, men who were better
        than you. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'So now the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is about to strike you, your
        people, your children, your wives, and all that is yours with a heavy blow. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "You yourself will suffer with a severe intestinal disease that will
        get worse each day until your bowels come out.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> stirred up the Philistines and
        the Arabs, who lived near the Ethiopians,[[COMMENT(0)]] to attack Jehoram. '
      comments:
      - number: '21:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Cushites.</b>
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "They marched against Judah, broke down its defenses, and carried
        away everything of value in the royal palace, including the king\u2019s sons
        and his wives. Only his youngest son, Ahaziah,[[COMMENT(0)]] was spared.  "
      comments:
      - number: '21:17 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Jehoahaz, </b>a variant spelling of Ahaziah; compare 22:1.
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'After all this, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> struck Jehoram with
        an incurable intestinal disease. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'The disease grew worse and worse, and at the end of two years it
        caused his bowels to come out, and he died in agony. His people did not build
        a great funeral fire to honor him as they had done for his ancestors.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: Jehoram was thirty-two years old when he became king, and he reigned
        in Jerusalem eight years. No one was sorry when he died. They buried him
        in the City of David, but not in the royal cemetery.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Ahaziah Rules in Judah'
      title: Ahaziah Rules in Judah
      number: 1
      content: "  Then the people of Jerusalem made Ahaziah, Jehoram\u2019s youngest
        son, their next king, since the marauding bands who came with the Arabs[[COMMENT(0)]]
        had killed all the older sons. So Ahaziah son of Jehoram reigned as king
        of Judah.  "
      comments:
      - number: '22:1 '
        content: Or <b>marauding bands of Arabs.</b>
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Ahaziah was twenty-two[[COMMENT(0)]] years old when he became king,
        and he reigned in Jerusalem one year. His mother was Athaliah, a granddaughter
        of King Omri. '
      comments:
      - number: '22:2 '
        content: As in some Greek manuscripts and Syriac version (see also 2 Kgs
          8:26); Hebrew reads <b>forty-two.</b>
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Ahaziah also followed the evil example of King Ahab\u2019s family,
        for his mother encouraged him in doing wrong. "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "He did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s sight,
        just as Ahab\u2019s family had done. They even became his advisers after
        the death of his father, and they led him to ruin.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Following their evil advice, Ahaziah joined Joram,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        the son of King Ahab of Israel, in his war against King Hazael of Aram at
        Ramoth-gilead. When the Arameans[[COMMENT(1)]] wounded Joram in the battle, '
      comments:
      - number: '22:5a '
        content: Hebrew <b>Jehoram, </b>a variant spelling of Joram; also in 22:6,
          7.
      - number: '22:5b '
        content: As in two Hebrew manuscripts and Latin Vulgate (see also 2 Kgs 8:28);
          Masoretic Text reads <b>the archers.</b>
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'he returned to Jezreel to recover from the wounds he had received
        at Ramoth.[[COMMENT(0)]] Because Joram was wounded, King Ahaziah[[COMMENT(1)]]
        of Judah went to Jezreel to visit him.  '
      comments:
      - number: '22:6a '
        content: Hebrew <b>Ramah, </b>a variant spelling of Ramoth.
      - number: '22:6b '
        content: As in some Hebrew manuscripts, Greek and Syriac versions, and Latin
          Vulgate (see also 2 Kgs 8:29); most Hebrew manuscripts read <b>Azariah.</b>
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "But God had decided that this visit would be Ahaziah\u2019s downfall.
        While he was there, Ahaziah went out with Joram to meet Jehu grandson of
        Nimshi,[[COMMENT(0)]] whom the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had appointed
        to destroy the dynasty of Ahab.  "
      comments:
      - number: '22:7 '
        content: Hebrew <b>descendant of Nimshi; </b>compare 2 Kgs 9:2, 14.
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "While Jehu was executing judgment against the family of Ahab, he
        happened to meet some of Judah\u2019s officials and Ahaziah\u2019s relatives[[COMMENT(0)]]
        who were traveling with Ahaziah. So Jehu killed them all. "
      comments:
      - number: '22:8 '
        content: As in Greek version (see also 2 Kgs 10:13); Hebrew reads <b>and
          sons of the brothers of Ahaziah.</b>
    - name: '9: Queen Athaliah Rules in Judah'
      title: Queen Athaliah Rules in Judah
      number: 9
      content: "Then Jehu\u2019s men searched for Ahaziah, and they found him hiding
        in the city of Samaria. They brought him to Jehu, who killed him. Ahaziah
        was given a decent burial because the people said, \u201CHe was the grandson
        of Jehoshaphat\u2014a man who sought the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> with
        all his heart.\u201D But none of the surviving members of Ahaziah\u2019s
        family was capable of ruling the kingdom.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "When Athaliah, the mother of King Ahaziah of Judah, learned that
        her son was dead, she began to destroy the rest of Judah\u2019s royal family. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "But Ahaziah\u2019s sister Jehosheba,[[COMMENT(0)]] the daughter of
        King Jehoram, took Ahaziah\u2019s infant son, Joash, and stole him away from
        among the rest of the king\u2019s children, who were about to be killed.
        She put Joash and his nurse in a bedroom. In this way, Jehosheba, wife of
        Jehoiada the priest and sister of Ahaziah, hid the child so that Athaliah
        could not murder him. "
      comments:
      - number: '22:11 '
        content: "As in parallel text at 2 Kgs 11:2; Hebrew lacks <b>Ahaziah\u2019s
          sister </b>and reads <b>Jehoshabeath </b>[a variant spelling of Jehosheba]."
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: Joash remained hidden in the Temple of God for six years while Athaliah
        ruled over the land.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Revolt against Athaliah'
      title: Revolt against Athaliah
      number: 1
      content: "  In the seventh year of Athaliah\u2019s reign, Jehoiada the priest
        decided to act. He summoned his courage and made a pact with five army commanders:
        Azariah son of Jeroham, Ishmael son of Jehohanan, Azariah son of Obed, Maaseiah
        son of Adaiah, and Elishaphat son of Zicri. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'These men traveled secretly throughout Judah and summoned the Levites
        and clan leaders in all the towns to come to Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "They all gathered at the Temple of God, where they made a solemn
        pact with Joash, the young king.Jehoiada said to them, \u201CHere is the
        king\u2019s son! The time has come for him to reign! The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has promised that a descendant of David will be our king. "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'This is what you must do. When you priests and Levites come on duty
        on the Sabbath, a third of you will serve as gatekeepers. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Another third will go over to the royal palace, and the final third
        will be at the Foundation Gate. Everyone else should stay in the courtyards
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Remember, only the priests and Levites on duty may enter the Temple
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, for they are set apart as holy. The rest
        of the people must obey the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s instructions
        and stay outside. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "You Levites, form a bodyguard around the king and keep your weapons
        in hand. Kill anyone who tries to enter the Temple. Stay with the king wherever
        he goes.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'So the Levites and all the people of Judah did everything as Jehoiada
        the priest ordered. The commanders took charge of the men reporting for duty
        that Sabbath, as well as those who were going off duty. Jehoiada the priest
        did not let anyone go home after their shift ended. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Then Jehoiada supplied the commanders with the spears and the large
        and small shields that had once belonged to King David and were stored in
        the Temple of God. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'He stationed all the people around the king, with their weapons ready.
        They formed a line from the south side of the Temple around to the north
        side and all around the altar.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: The Death of Athaliah'
      title: The Death of Athaliah
      number: 11
      content: "Then Jehoiada and his sons brought out Joash, the king\u2019s son,
        placed the crown on his head, and presented him with a copy of God\u2019s
        laws.[[COMMENT(0)]] They anointed him and proclaimed him king, and everyone
        shouted, \u201CLong live the king!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '23:11 '
        content: Or <b>a copy of the covenant.</b>
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "When Athaliah heard the noise of the people running and the shouts
        of praise to the king, she hurried to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple to see what was happening. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "When she arrived, she saw the newly crowned king standing in his
        place of authority by the pillar at the Temple entrance. The commanders and
        trumpeters were surrounding him, and people from all over the land were rejoicing
        and blowing trumpets. Singers with musical instruments were leading the people
        in a great celebration. When Athaliah saw all this, she tore her clothes
        in despair and shouted, \u201CTreason! Treason!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Then Jehoiada the priest ordered the commanders who were in charge
        of the troops, \u201CTake her to the soldiers in front of the Temple,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and kill anyone who tries to rescue her.\u201D For the priest had said, \u201CShe
        must not be killed in the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '23:14 '
        content: Or <b>Bring her out from between the ranks; </b>or <b>Take her out
          of the Temple precincts. </b>The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - name: "15: Jehoiada\u2019s Religious Reforms"
      title: "Jehoiada\u2019s Religious Reforms"
      number: 15
      content: 'So they seized her and led her out to the entrance of the Horse Gate
        on the palace grounds, and they killed her there.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Then Jehoiada made a covenant between himself and the king and the
        people that they would be the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s people. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'And all the people went over to the temple of Baal and tore it down.
        They demolished the altars and smashed the idols, and they killed Mattan
        the priest of Baal in front of the altars.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Jehoiada now put the priests and Levites in charge of the Temple
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, following all the directions given by
        David. He also commanded them to present burnt offerings to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        as prescribed by the Law of Moses, and to sing and rejoice as David had instructed. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "He also stationed gatekeepers at the gates of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple to keep out those who for any reason were ceremonially unclean.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Then the commanders, nobles, rulers, and all the people of the land
        escorted the king from the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. They
        went through the upper gate and into the palace, and they seated the king
        on the royal throne. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: So all the people of the land rejoiced, and the city was peaceful
        because Athaliah had been killed.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Joash Repairs the Temple'
      title: Joash Repairs the Temple
      number: 1
      content: '  Joash was seven years old when he became king, and he reigned in
        Jerusalem forty years. His mother was Zibiah from Beersheba. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Joash did what was pleasing in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight throughout the lifetime of Jehoiada the priest. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Jehoiada chose two wives for Joash, and he had sons and daughters.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'At one point Joash decided to repair and restore the Temple of the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "He summoned the priests and Levites and gave them these instructions:
        \u201CGo to all the towns of Judah and collect the required annual offerings,
        so that we can repair the Temple of your God. Do not delay!\u201D But the
        Levites did not act immediately.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "So the king called for Jehoiada the high priest and asked him, \u201CWhy
        haven\u2019t you demanded that the Levites go out and collect the Temple
        taxes from the towns of Judah and from Jerusalem? Moses, the servant of the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, levied this tax on the community of Israel in
        order to maintain the Tabernacle of the Covenant.[[COMMENT(0)]]\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '24:6 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Tent of the Testimony.</b>
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Over the years the followers of wicked Athaliah had broken into the
        Temple of God, and they had used all the dedicated things from the Temple
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> to worship the images of Baal.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'So now the king ordered a chest to be made and set outside the gate
        leading to the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Then a proclamation was sent throughout Judah and Jerusalem, telling
        the people to bring to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> the tax that Moses,
        the servant of God, had required of the Israelites in the wilderness. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'This pleased all the leaders and the people, and they gladly brought
        their money and filled the chest with it.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Whenever the chest became full, the Levites would carry it to the
        king\u2019s officials. Then the court secretary and an officer of the high
        priest would come and empty the chest and take it back to the Temple again.
        This went on day after day, and a large amount of money was collected. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "The king and Jehoiada gave the money to the construction supervisors,
        who hired masons and carpenters to restore the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        They also hired metalworkers, who made articles of iron and bronze for the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'The men in charge of the renovation worked hard and made steady progress.
        They restored the Temple of God according to its original design and strengthened
        it. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "When all the repairs were finished, they brought the remaining money
        to the king and Jehoiada. It was used to make various articles for the Temple
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2014articles for worship services and
        for burnt offerings, including ladles and other articles made of gold and
        silver. And the burnt offerings were sacrificed continually in the Temple
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> during the lifetime of Jehoiada the priest.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Jehoiada lived to a very old age, finally dying at 130. '
      comments: []
    - name: "16: Jehoiada\u2019s Reforms Reversed"
      title: "Jehoiada\u2019s Reforms Reversed"
      number: 16
      content: 'He was buried among the kings in the City of David, because he had
        done so much good in Israel for God and his Temple.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "But after Jehoiada\u2019s death, the leaders of Judah came and bowed
        before King Joash and persuaded him to listen to their advice. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'They decided to abandon the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of their ancestors, and they worshiped Asherah poles and idols instead!
        Because of this sin, divine anger fell on Judah and Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'Yet the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> sent prophets to bring them back
        to him. The prophets warned them, but still the people would not listen.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Then the Spirit of God came upon Zechariah son of Jehoiada the priest.
        He stood before the people and said, \u201CThis is what God says: Why do
        you disobey the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s commands and keep yourselves
        from prospering? You have abandoned the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, and
        now he has abandoned you!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Then the leaders plotted to kill Zechariah, and King Joash ordered
        that they stone him to death in the courtyard of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple. "
      comments: []
    - name: "22: The End of Joash\u2019s Reign"
      title: "The End of Joash\u2019s Reign"
      number: 22
      content: "That was how King Joash repaid Jehoiada for his loyalty\u2014by killing
        his son. Zechariah\u2019s last words as he died were, \u201CMay the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        see what they are doing and avenge my death!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'In the spring of the year[[COMMENT(0)]] the Aramean army marched
        against Joash. They invaded Judah and Jerusalem and killed all the leaders
        of the nation. Then they sent all the plunder back to their king in Damascus. '
      comments:
      - number: '24:23 '
        content: Hebrew <b>At the turn of the year. </b>The first day of the year
          in the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar occurred in March or April.
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'Although the Arameans attacked with only a small army, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        helped them conquer the much larger army of Judah. The people of Judah had
        abandoned the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of their ancestors, so
        judgment was carried out against Joash.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'The Arameans withdrew, leaving Joash severely wounded. But his own
        officials plotted to kill him for murdering the son[[COMMENT(0)]] of Jehoiada
        the priest. They assassinated him as he lay in bed. Then he was buried in
        the City of David, but not in the royal cemetery. '
      comments:
      - number: '24:25 '
        content: As in Greek version and Latin Vulgate; Hebrew reads <b>sons.</b>
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'The assassins were Jozacar,[[COMMENT(0)]] the son of an Ammonite
        woman named Shimeath, and Jehozabad, the son of a Moabite woman named Shomer.[[COMMENT(1)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '24:26a '
        content: As in parallel text at 2 Kgs 12:21; Hebrew reads <b>Zabad.</b>
      - number: '24:26b '
        content: As in parallel text at 2 Kgs 12:21; Hebrew reads <b>Shimrith, </b>a
          variant spelling of Shomer.
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: The account of the sons of Joash, the prophecies about him, and the
        record of his restoration of the Temple of God are written in The Commentary
        on the Book of the Kings. His son Amaziah became the next king.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Amaziah Rules in Judah'
      title: Amaziah Rules in Judah
      number: 1
      content: '  Amaziah was twenty-five years old when he became king, and he reigned
        in Jerusalem twenty-nine years. His mother was Jehoaddin[[COMMENT(0)]] from
        Jerusalem. '
      comments:
      - number: '25:1 '
        content: As in parallel text at 2 Kgs 14:2; Hebrew reads <b>Jehoaddan, </b>a
          variant spelling of Jehoaddin.
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Amaziah did what was pleasing in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight, but not wholeheartedly.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'When Amaziah was well established as king, he executed the officials
        who had assassinated his father. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "However, he did not kill the children of the assassins, for he obeyed
        the command of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> as written by Moses in the
        Book of the Law: \u201CParents must not be put to death for the sins of their
        children, nor children for the sins of their parents. Those deserving to
        die must be put to death for their own crimes.\u201D[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '25:4 '
        content: Deut 24:16.
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Then Amaziah organized the army, assigning generals and captains[[COMMENT(0)]]
        for all Judah and Benjamin. He took a census and found that he had an army
        of 300,000 select troops, twenty years old and older, all trained in the
        use of spear and shield. '
      comments:
      - number: '25:5 '
        content: Hebrew <b>commanders of thousands and commanders of hundreds.</b>
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'He also paid about 7,500 pounds[[COMMENT(0)]] of silver to hire 100,000
        experienced fighting men from Israel.  '
      comments:
      - number: '25:6 '
        content: Hebrew <b>100 talents </b>[3,400 kilograms].
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "But a man of God came to him and said, \u201CYour Majesty, do not
        hire troops from Israel, for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is not with
        Israel. He will not help those people of Ephraim! "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "If you let them go with your troops into battle, you will be defeated
        by the enemy no matter how well you fight. God will overthrow you, for he
        has the power to help you or to trip you up.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Amaziah asked the man of God, \u201CBut what about all that silver
        I paid to hire the army of Israel?\u201DThe man of God replied, \u201CThe
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is able to give you much more than this!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'So Amaziah discharged the hired troops and sent them back to Ephraim.
        This made them very angry with Judah, and they returned home in a great rage.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Then Amaziah summoned his courage and led his army to the Valley
        of Salt, where they killed 10,000 Edomite troops from Seir. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'They captured another 10,000 and took them to the top of a cliff
        and threw them off, dashing them to pieces on the rocks below.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Meanwhile, the hired troops that Amaziah had sent home raided several
        of the towns of Judah between Samaria and Beth-horon. They killed 3,000 people
        and carried off great quantities of plunder.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'When King Amaziah returned from slaughtering the Edomites, he brought
        with him idols taken from the people of Seir. He set them up as his own gods,
        bowed down in front of them, and offered sacrifices to them! '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "This made the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> very angry, and he sent
        a prophet to ask, \u201CWhy do you turn to gods who could not even save their
        own people from you?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "But the king interrupted him and said, \u201CSince when have I made
        you the king\u2019s counselor? Be quiet now before I have you killed!\u201DSo
        the prophet stopped with this warning: \u201CI know that God has determined
        to destroy you because you have done this and have refused to accept my counsel.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "After consulting with his advisers, King Amaziah of Judah sent this
        challenge to Israel\u2019s king Jehoash,[[COMMENT(0)]] the son of Jehoahaz
        and grandson of Jehu: \u201CCome and meet me in battle!\u201D[[COMMENT(1)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '25:17a '
        content: Hebrew <b>Joash, </b>a variant spelling of Jehoash; also in 25:18,
          21, 23, 25.
      - number: '25:17b '
        content: Hebrew <b>Come, let us look one another in the face.</b>
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "But King Jehoash of Israel replied to King Amaziah of Judah with
        this story: \u201COut in the Lebanon mountains, a thistle sent a message
        to a mighty cedar tree: \u2018Give your daughter in marriage to my son.\u2019
        But just then a wild animal of Lebanon came by and stepped on the thistle,
        crushing it!  "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "\u201CYou are saying, \u2018I have defeated Edom,\u2019 and you are
        very proud of it. But my advice is to stay at home. Why stir up trouble that
        will only bring disaster on you and the people of Judah?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'But Amaziah refused to listen, for God was determined to destroy
        him for turning to the gods of Edom. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'So King Jehoash of Israel mobilized his army against King Amaziah
        of Judah. The two armies drew up their battle lines at Beth-shemesh in Judah. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'Judah was routed by the army of Israel, and its army scattered and
        fled for home. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "King Jehoash of Israel captured Judah\u2019s king, Amaziah son of
        Joash and grandson of Ahaziah, at Beth-shemesh. Then he brought him to Jerusalem,
        where he demolished 600 feet[[COMMENT(0)]] of Jerusalem\u2019s wall, from
        the Ephraim Gate to the Corner Gate. "
      comments:
      - number: '25:23 '
        content: Hebrew <b>400 cubits </b>[180 meters].
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'He carried off all the gold and silver and all the articles from
        the Temple of God that had been in the care of Obed-edom. He also seized
        the treasures of the royal palace, along with hostages, and then returned
        to Samaria.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'King Amaziah of Judah lived for fifteen years after the death of
        King Jehoash of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "The rest of the events in Amaziah\u2019s reign, from beginning to
        end, are recorded in The Book of the Kings of Judah and Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'After Amaziah turned away from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, there
        was a conspiracy against his life in Jerusalem, and he fled to Lachish. But
        his enemies sent assassins after him, and they killed him there. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: They brought his body back on a horse, and he was buried with his
        ancestors in the City of David.[[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: '25:28 '
        content: As in some Hebrew manuscripts and other ancient versions (see also
          2 Kgs 14:20); most Hebrew manuscripts read <b>the city of Judah.</b>
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Uzziah Rules in Judah'
      title: Uzziah Rules in Judah
      number: 1
      content: "  All the people of Judah had crowned Amaziah\u2019s sixteen-year-old
        son, Uzziah, as king in place of his father. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "After his father\u2019s death, Uzziah rebuilt the town of Elath[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and restored it to Judah.  "
      comments:
      - number: '26:2 '
        content: As in Greek version (see also 2 Kgs 14:22; 16:6); Hebrew reads <b>Eloth,
          </b>a variant spelling of Elath.
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Uzziah was sixteen years old when he became king, and he reigned
        in Jerusalem fifty-two years. His mother was Jecoliah from Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "He did what was pleasing in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight, just as his father, Amaziah, had done. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Uzziah sought God during the days of Zechariah, who taught him to
        fear God.[[COMMENT(0)]] And as long as the king sought guidance from the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, God gave him success.  '
      comments:
      - number: '26:5 '
        content: As in Syriac and Greek versions; Hebrew reads <b>who instructed
          him in divine visions.</b>
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Uzziah declared war on the Philistines and broke down the walls of
        Gath, Jabneh, and Ashdod. Then he built new towns in the Ashdod area and
        in other parts of Philistia. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'God helped him in his wars against the Philistines, his battles with
        the Arabs of Gur,[[COMMENT(0)]] and his wars with the Meunites. '
      comments:
      - number: '26:7 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>Gur-baal.</b>
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'The Meunites[[COMMENT(0)]] paid annual tribute to him, and his fame
        spread even to Egypt, for he had become very powerful.  '
      comments:
      - number: '26:8 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>Ammonites. </b>Compare 26:7.
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Uzziah built fortified towers in Jerusalem at the Corner Gate, at
        the Valley Gate, and at the angle in the wall. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'He also constructed forts in the wilderness and dug many water cisterns,
        because he kept great herds of livestock in the foothills of Judah[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and on the plains. He was also a man who loved the soil. He had many workers
        who cared for his farms and vineyards, both on the hillsides and in the fertile
        valleys.  '
      comments:
      - number: '26:10 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Shephelah.</b>
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Uzziah had an army of well-trained warriors, ready to march into
        battle, unit by unit. This army had been mustered and organized by Jeiel,
        the secretary of the army, and his assistant, Maaseiah. They were under the
        direction of Hananiah, one of the king\u2019s officials. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'These regiments of mighty warriors were commanded by 2,600 clan leaders. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'The army consisted of 307,500 men, all elite troops. They were prepared
        to assist the king against any enemy.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Uzziah provided the entire army with shields, spears, helmets, coats
        of mail, bows, and sling stones. '
      comments: []
    - name: "15: Uzziah\u2019s Sin and Punishment"
      title: "Uzziah\u2019s Sin and Punishment"
      number: 15
      content: 'And he built structures on the walls of Jerusalem, designed by experts
        to protect those who shot arrows and hurled large stones[[COMMENT(0)]] from
        the towers and the corners of the wall. His fame spread far and wide, for
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> gave him marvelous help, and he became very
        powerful.  '
      comments:
      - number: '26:15 '
        content: Or <b>to shoot arrows and hurl large stones.</b>
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "But when he had become powerful, he also became proud, which led
        to his downfall. He sinned against the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> his God
        by entering the sanctuary of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple
        and personally burning incense on the incense altar. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Azariah the high priest went in after him with eighty other priests
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, all brave men. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "They confronted King Uzziah and said, \u201CIt is not for you, Uzziah,
        to burn incense to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. That is the work of the
        priests alone, the descendants of Aaron who are set apart for this work.
        Get out of the sanctuary, for you have sinned. The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        God will not honor you for this!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Uzziah, who was holding an incense burner, became furious. But as
        he was standing there raging at the priests before the incense altar in the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple, leprosy[[COMMENT(0)]] suddenly
        broke out on his forehead. "
      comments:
      - number: '26:19 '
        content: Or <b>a contagious skin disease. </b>The Hebrew word used here and
          throughout this passage can describe various skin diseases.
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'When Azariah the high priest and all the other priests saw the leprosy,
        they rushed him out. And the king himself was eager to get out because the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had struck him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'So King Uzziah had leprosy until the day he died. He lived in isolation
        in a separate house, for he was excluded from the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        His son Jotham was put in charge of the royal palace, and he governed the
        people of the land.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "The rest of the events of Uzziah\u2019s reign, from beginning to
        end, are recorded by the prophet Isaiah son of Amoz. "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "When Uzziah died, he was buried with his ancestors; his grave was
        in a nearby burial field belonging to the kings, for the people said, \u201CHe
        had leprosy.\u201D And his son Jotham became the next king."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Jotham Rules in Judah'
      title: Jotham Rules in Judah
      number: 1
      content: '  Jotham was twenty-five years old when he became king, and he reigned
        in Jerusalem sixteen years. His mother was Jerusha, the daughter of Zadok.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Jotham did what was pleasing in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight. He did everything his father, Uzziah, had done, except that Jotham
        did not sin by entering the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. But
        the people continued in their corrupt ways.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Jotham rebuilt the upper gate of the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        He also did extensive rebuilding on the wall at the hill of Ophel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'He built towns in the hill country of Judah and constructed fortresses
        and towers in the wooded areas. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Jotham went to war against the Ammonites and conquered them. Over
        the next three years he received from them an annual tribute of 7,500 pounds[[COMMENT(0)]]
        of silver, 50,000 bushels of wheat, and 50,000 bushels of barley.[[COMMENT(1)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '27:5a '
        content: Hebrew <b>100 talents </b>[3,400 kilograms].
      - number: '27:5b '
        content: Hebrew <b>10,000 cors </b>[2,200 kiloliters] <b>of wheat, and 10,000
          cors of barley.</b>
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'King Jotham became powerful because he was careful to live in obedience
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> his God.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "The rest of the events of Jotham\u2019s reign, including all his
        wars and other activities, are recorded in The Book of the Kings of Israel
        and Judah.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'He was twenty-five years old when he became king, and he reigned
        in Jerusalem sixteen years. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: When Jotham died, he was buried in the City of David. And his son
        Ahaz became the next king.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Ahaz Rules in Judah'
      title: Ahaz Rules in Judah
      number: 1
      content: '  Ahaz was twenty years old when he became king, and he reigned in
        Jerusalem sixteen years. He did not do what was pleasing in the sight of
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, as his ancestor David had done. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Instead, he followed the example of the kings of Israel. He cast
        metal images for the worship of Baal. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'He offered sacrifices in the valley of Ben-Hinnom, even sacrificing
        his own sons in the fire.[[COMMENT(0)]] In this way, he followed the detestable
        practices of the pagan nations the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had driven
        from the land ahead of the Israelites. '
      comments:
      - number: '28:3 '
        content: Or <b>even making his sons pass through the fire.</b>
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'He offered sacrifices and burned incense at the pagan shrines and
        on the hills and under every green tree.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Because of all this, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> his God allowed
        the king of Aram to defeat Ahaz and to exile large numbers of his people
        to Damascus. The armies of the king of Israel also defeated Ahaz and inflicted
        many casualties on his army. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "In a single day Pekah son of Remaliah, Israel\u2019s king, killed
        120,000 of Judah\u2019s troops, all of them experienced warriors, because
        they had abandoned the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of their ancestors. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Then Zicri, a warrior from Ephraim, killed Maaseiah, the king\u2019s
        son; Azrikam, the king\u2019s palace commander; and Elkanah, the king\u2019s
        second-in-command. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'The armies of Israel captured 200,000 women and children from Judah
        and seized tremendous amounts of plunder, which they took back to Samaria.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "But a prophet of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> named Oded was there
        in Samaria when the army of Israel returned home. He went out to meet them
        and said, \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of your ancestors,
        was angry with Judah and let you defeat them. But you have gone too far,
        killing them without mercy, and all heaven is disturbed. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'And now you are planning to make slaves of these people from Judah
        and Jerusalem. What about your own sins against the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God? '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Listen to me and return these prisoners you have taken, for they
        are your own relatives. Watch out, because now the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        fierce anger has been turned against you!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Then some of the leaders of Israel[[COMMENT(0)]]\u2014Azariah son
        of Jehohanan, Berekiah son of Meshillemoth, Jehizkiah son of Shallum, and
        Amasa son of Hadlai\u2014agreed with this and confronted the men returning
        from battle. "
      comments:
      - number: '28:12 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Ephraim, </b>referring to the northern kingdom of Israel.
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201CYou must not bring the prisoners here!\u201D they declared.
        \u201CWe cannot afford to add to our sins and guilt. Our guilt is already
        great, and the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s fierce anger is already
        turned against Israel.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'So the warriors released the prisoners and handed over the plunder
        in the sight of the leaders and all the people. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: Ahaz Closes the Temple'
      title: Ahaz Closes the Temple
      number: 15
      content: 'Then the four men just mentioned by name came forward and distributed
        clothes from the plunder to the prisoners who were naked. They provided clothing
        and sandals to wear, gave them enough food and drink, and dressed their wounds
        with olive oil. They put those who were weak on donkeys and took all the
        prisoners back to their own people in Jericho, the city of palms. Then they
        returned to Samaria.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'At that time King Ahaz of Judah asked the king of Assyria for help. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'The armies of Edom had again invaded Judah and taken captives. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'And the Philistines had raided towns located in the foothills of
        Judah[[COMMENT(0)]] and in the Negev of Judah. They had already captured
        and occupied Beth-shemesh, Aijalon, Gederoth, Soco with its villages, Timnah
        with its villages, and Gimzo with its villages. '
      comments:
      - number: '28:18 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Shephelah.</b>
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was humbling Judah because of King
        Ahaz of Judah,[[COMMENT(0)]] for he had encouraged his people to sin and
        had been utterly unfaithful to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments:
      - number: '28:19 '
        content: Masoretic Text reads <b>of Israel; </b>also in 28:23, 27. The author
          of Chronicles sees Judah as representative of the true Israel. (Some Hebrew
          manuscripts and Greek version read <b>of Judah.</b>)
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'So when King Tiglath-pileser[[COMMENT(0)]] of Assyria arrived, he
        attacked Ahaz instead of helping him. '
      comments:
      - number: '28:20 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Tilgath-pilneser, </b>a variant spelling of Tiglath-pileser.
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Ahaz took valuable items from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple, the royal palace, and from the homes of his officials and gave them
        to the king of Assyria as tribute. But this did not help him.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'Even during this time of trouble, King Ahaz continued to reject the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "He offered sacrifices to the gods of Damascus who had defeated him,
        for he said, \u201CSince these gods helped the kings of Aram, they will help
        me, too, if I sacrifice to them.\u201D But instead, they led to his ruin
        and the ruin of all Judah.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "The king took the various articles from the Temple of God and broke
        them into pieces. He shut the doors of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple so that no one could worship there, and he set up altars to pagan
        gods in every corner of Jerusalem. "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'He made pagan shrines in all the towns of Judah for offering sacrifices
        to other gods. In this way, he aroused the anger of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of his ancestors.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "The rest of the events of Ahaz\u2019s reign and everything he did,
        from beginning to end, are recorded in The Book of the Kings of Judah and
        Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: When Ahaz died, he was buried in Jerusalem but not in the royal cemetery
        of the kings of Judah. Then his son Hezekiah became the next king.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Hezekiah Rules in Judah'
      title: Hezekiah Rules in Judah
      number: 1
      content: '  Hezekiah was twenty-five years old when he became the king of Judah,
        and he reigned in Jerusalem twenty-nine years. His mother was Abijah, the
        daughter of Zechariah. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: Hezekiah Reopens the Temple'
      title: Hezekiah Reopens the Temple
      number: 2
      content: "He did what was pleasing in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight, just as his ancestor David had done.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'In the very first month of the first year of his reign, Hezekiah
        reopened the doors of the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and repaired
        them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'He summoned the priests and Levites to meet him at the courtyard
        east of the Temple. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "He said to them, \u201CListen to me, you Levites! Purify yourselves,
        and purify the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of your
        ancestors. Remove all the defiled things from the sanctuary. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Our ancestors were unfaithful and did what was evil in the sight
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> our God. They abandoned the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and his dwelling place; they turned their backs on him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "They also shut the doors to the Temple\u2019s entry room, and they
        snuffed out the lamps. They stopped burning incense and presenting burnt
        offerings at the sanctuary of the God of Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201CThat is why the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s anger has
        fallen upon Judah and Jerusalem. He has made them an object of dread, horror,
        and ridicule, as you can see with your own eyes. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Because of this, our fathers have been killed in battle, and our
        sons and daughters and wives have been captured. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'But now I will make a covenant with the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel, so that his fierce anger will turn away from us. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "My sons, do not neglect your duties any longer! The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has chosen you to stand in his presence, to minister to him, and to lead
        the people in worship and present offerings to him.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'Then these Levites got right to work:From the clan of Kohath: Mahath
        son of Amasai and Joel son of Azariah.From the clan of Merari: Kish son of
        Abdi and Azariah son of Jehallelel.From the clan of Gershon: Joah son of
        Zimmah and Eden son of Joah.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'From the family of Elizaphan: Shimri and Jeiel.From the family of
        Asaph: Zechariah and Mattaniah.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'From the family of Heman: Jehiel and Shimei.From the family of Jeduthun:
        Shemaiah and Uzziel.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "These men called together their fellow Levites, and they all purified
        themselves. Then they began to cleanse the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        just as the king had commanded. They were careful to follow all the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        instructions in their work. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'The priests went into the sanctuary of the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        to cleanse it, and they took out to the Temple courtyard all the defiled
        things they found. From there the Levites carted it all out to the Kidron
        Valley.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: The Temple Rededication'
      title: The Temple Rededication
      number: 17
      content: "They began the work in early spring, on the first day of the new
        year,[[COMMENT(0)]] and in eight days they had reached the entry room of
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple. Then they purified the Temple
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> itself, which took another eight days.
        So the entire task was completed in sixteen days.  "
      comments:
      - number: '29:17 '
        content: Hebrew <b>on the first day of the first month. </b>This day in the
          ancient Hebrew lunar calendar occurred in March or early April, 715 <span
          class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Then the Levites went to King Hezekiah and gave him this report:
        \u201CWe have cleansed the entire Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the altar of burnt offering with all its utensils, and the table of the Bread
        of the Presence with all its utensils. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "We have also recovered all the items discarded by King Ahaz when
        he was unfaithful and closed the Temple. They are now in front of the altar
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, purified and ready for use.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Early the next morning King Hezekiah gathered the city officials
        and went to the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'They brought seven bulls, seven rams, and seven male lambs as a burnt
        offering, together with seven male goats as a sin offering for the kingdom,
        for the Temple, and for Judah. The king commanded the priests, who were descendants
        of Aaron, to sacrifice the animals on the altar of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'So they killed the bulls, and the priests took the blood and sprinkled
        it on the altar. Next they killed the rams and sprinkled their blood on the
        altar. And finally, they did the same with the male lambs. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'The male goats for the sin offering were then brought before the
        king and the assembly of people, who laid their hands on them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'The priests then killed the goats as a sin offering and sprinkled
        their blood on the altar to make atonement for the sins of all Israel. The
        king had specifically commanded that this burnt offering and sin offering
        should be made for all Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "King Hezekiah then stationed the Levites at the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        with cymbals, lyres, and harps. He obeyed all the commands that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had given to King David through Gad, the king\u2019s seer, and the prophet
        Nathan. "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'The Levites then took their positions around the Temple with the
        instruments of David, and the priests took their positions with the trumpets.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'Then Hezekiah ordered that the burnt offering be placed on the altar.
        As the burnt offering was presented, songs of praise to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        were begun, accompanied by the trumpets and other instruments of David, the
        former king of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'The entire assembly worshiped the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> as
        the singers sang and the trumpets blew, until all the burnt offerings were
        finished. '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'Then the king and everyone with him bowed down in worship. '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'King Hezekiah and the officials ordered the Levites to praise the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> with the psalms written by David and by Asaph
        the seer. So they offered joyous praise and bowed down in worship.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "Then Hezekiah declared, \u201CNow that you have consecrated yourselves
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, bring your sacrifices and thanksgiving
        offerings to the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201D So the
        people brought their sacrifices and thanksgiving offerings, and all whose
        hearts were willing brought burnt offerings, too. "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'The people brought to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> 70 bulls, 100
        rams, and 200 male lambs for burnt offerings. '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'They also brought 600 cattle and 3,000 sheep and goats as sacred
        offerings.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: 'But there were too few priests to prepare all the burnt offerings.
        So their relatives the Levites helped them until the work was finished and
        more priests had been purified, for the Levites had been more conscientious
        about purifying themselves than the priests had been. '
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: 'There was an abundance of burnt offerings, along with the usual liquid
        offerings, and a great deal of fat from the many peace offerings.So the Temple
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was restored to service. '
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: And Hezekiah and all the people rejoiced because of what God had done
        for the people, for everything had been accomplished so quickly.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Preparations for Passover'
      title: Preparations for Passover
      number: 1
      content: '  King Hezekiah now sent word to all Israel and Judah, and he wrote
        letters of invitation to the people of Ephraim and Manasseh. He asked everyone
        to come to the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> at Jerusalem to
        celebrate the Passover of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'The king, his officials, and all the community of Jerusalem decided
        to celebrate Passover a month later than usual.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '30:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>in the second month. </b>Passover was normally observed
          in the first month (of the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar).
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'They were unable to celebrate it at the prescribed time because not
        enough priests could be purified by then, and the people had not yet assembled
        at Jerusalem.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'This plan for keeping the Passover seemed right to the king and all
        the people. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'So they sent a proclamation throughout all Israel, from Beersheba
        in the south to Dan in the north, inviting everyone to come to Jerusalem
        to celebrate the Passover of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of
        Israel. The people had not been celebrating it in great numbers as required
        in the Law.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "At the king\u2019s command, runners were sent throughout Israel and
        Judah. They carried letters that said:\u201CO people of Israel, return to
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Israel,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        so that he will return to the few of us who have survived the conquest of
        the Assyrian kings. "
      comments:
      - number: '30:6 '
        content: <b>Israel </b>is the name that God gave to Jacob.
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Do not be like your ancestors and relatives who abandoned the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of their ancestors, and became an object of derision, as you yourselves
        can see. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Do not be stubborn, as they were, but submit yourselves to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        Come to his Temple, which he has set apart as holy forever. Worship the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God so that his fierce anger will turn away from you.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: Celebration of Passover'
      title: Celebration of Passover
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CFor if you return to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, your
        relatives and your children will be treated mercifully by their captors,
        and they will be able to return to this land. For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God is gracious and merciful. If you return to him, he will not continue
        to turn his face from you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'The runners went from town to town throughout Ephraim and Manasseh
        and as far as the territory of Zebulun. But most of the people just laughed
        at the runners and made fun of them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'However, some people from Asher, Manasseh, and Zebulun humbled themselves
        and went to Jerusalem.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "At the same time, God\u2019s hand was on the people in the land of
        Judah, giving them all one heart to obey the orders of the king and his officials,
        who were following the word of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'So a huge crowd assembled at Jerusalem in midspring[[COMMENT(0)]]
        to celebrate the Festival of Unleavened Bread. '
      comments:
      - number: '30:13 '
        content: Hebrew <b>in the second month. </b>The second month of the ancient
          Hebrew lunar calendar usually occurs within the months of April and May.
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'They set to work and removed the pagan altars from Jerusalem. They
        took away all the incense altars and threw them into the Kidron Valley.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'On the fourteenth day of the second month, one month later than usual,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        the people slaughtered the Passover lamb. This shamed the priests and Levites,
        so they purified themselves and brought burnt offerings to the Temple of
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments:
      - number: '30:15 '
        content: Hebrew <b>On the fourteenth day of the second month. </b>Passover
          normally began on the fourteenth day of the first month (see Lev 23:5).
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Then they took their places at the Temple as prescribed in the Law
        of Moses, the man of God. The Levites brought the sacrificial blood to the
        priests, who then sprinkled it on the altar.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Since many of the people had not purified themselves, the Levites
        had to slaughter their Passover lamb for them, to set them apart for the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Most of those who came from Ephraim, Manasseh, Issachar, and Zebulun
        had not purified themselves. But King Hezekiah prayed for them, and they
        were allowed to eat the Passover meal anyway, even though this was contrary
        to the requirements of the Law. For Hezekiah said, \u201CMay the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        who is good, pardon those "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "who decide to follow the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of
        their ancestors, even though they are not properly cleansed for the ceremony.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> listened to Hezekiah\u2019s prayer
        and healed the people.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: So the people of Israel who were present in Jerusalem joyously celebrated
        the Festival of Unleavened Bread for seven days. Each day the Levites and
        priests sang to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, accompanied by loud instruments.[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps>
      comments:
      - number: '30:21 '
        content: Or <b>sang to the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>
          with all their strength.</b>
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'Hezekiah encouraged all the Levites regarding the skill they displayed
        as they served the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. The celebration continued
        for seven days. Peace offerings were sacrificed, and the people gave thanks
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of their ancestors.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'The entire assembly then decided to continue the festival another
        seven days, so they celebrated joyfully for another week. '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'King Hezekiah gave the people 1,000 bulls and 7,000 sheep and goats
        for offerings, and the officials donated 1,000 bulls and 10,000 sheep and
        goats. Meanwhile, many more priests purified themselves.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'The entire assembly of Judah rejoiced, including the priests, the
        Levites, all who came from the land of Israel, the foreigners who came to
        the festival, and all those who lived in Judah. '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "There was great joy in the city, for Jerusalem had not seen a celebration
        like this one since the days of Solomon, King David\u2019s son. "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: Then the priests and Levites stood and blessed the people, and God
        heard their prayer from his holy dwelling in heaven.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Hezekiah\u2019s Religious Reforms"
      title: "Hezekiah\u2019s Religious Reforms"
      number: 1
      content: '  When the festival ended, the Israelites who attended went to all
        the towns of Judah, Benjamin, Ephraim, and Manasseh, and they smashed all
        the sacred pillars, cut down the Asherah poles, and removed the pagan shrines
        and altars. After this, the Israelites returned to their own towns and homes.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Hezekiah then organized the priests and Levites into divisions to
        offer the burnt offerings and peace offerings, and to worship and give thanks
        and praise to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> at the gates of the Temple. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'The king also made a personal contribution of animals for the daily
        morning and evening burnt offerings, the weekly Sabbath festivals, the monthly
        new moon festivals, and the annual festivals as prescribed in the Law of
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'In addition, he required the people in Jerusalem to bring a portion
        of their goods to the priests and Levites, so they could devote themselves
        fully to the Law of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "When the people of Israel heard these requirements, they responded
        generously by bringing the first share of their grain, new wine, olive oil,
        honey, and all the produce of their fields. They brought a large quantity\u2014a
        tithe of all they produced. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'The people who had moved to Judah from Israel, and the people of
        Judah themselves, brought in the tithes of their cattle, sheep, and goats
        and a tithe of the things that had been dedicated to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        their God, and they piled them up in great heaps. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'They began piling them up in late spring, and the heaps continued
        to grow until early autumn.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '31:7 '
        content: Hebrew <b>in the third month . . . until the seventh month. </b>The
          third month of the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar usually occurs within
          the months of May and June; the seventh month usually occurs within September
          and October.
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'When Hezekiah and his officials came and saw these huge piles, they
        thanked the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and his people Israel!  '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CWhere did all this come from?\u201D Hezekiah asked the priests
        and Levites.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "And Azariah the high priest, from the family of Zadok, replied, \u201CSince
        the people began bringing their gifts to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple, we have had enough to eat and plenty to spare. The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has blessed his people, and all this is left over.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Hezekiah ordered that storerooms be prepared in the Temple of the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. When this was done, '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'the people faithfully brought all the gifts, tithes, and other items
        dedicated for use in the Temple. Conaniah the Levite was put in charge, assisted
        by his brother Shimei. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'The supervisors under them were Jehiel, Azaziah, Nahath, Asahel,
        Jerimoth, Jozabad, Eliel, Ismakiah, Mahath, and Benaiah. These appointments
        were made by King Hezekiah and Azariah, the chief official in the Temple
        of God.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Kore son of Imnah the Levite, who was the gatekeeper at the East
        Gate, was put in charge of distributing the voluntary offerings given to
        God, the gifts, and the things that had been dedicated to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'His faithful assistants were Eden, Miniamin, Jeshua, Shemaiah, Amariah,
        and Shecaniah. They distributed the gifts among the families of priests in
        their towns by their divisions, dividing the gifts fairly among old and young
        alike. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "They distributed the gifts to all males three years old or older,
        regardless of their place in the genealogical records. The distribution went
        to all who would come to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple to
        perform their daily duties according to their divisions. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'They distributed gifts to the priests who were listed by their families
        in the genealogical records, and to the Levites twenty years old or older
        who were listed according to their jobs and their divisions. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Food allotments were also given to the families of all those listed
        in the genealogical records, including their little babies, wives, sons,
        and daughters. For they had all been faithful in purifying themselves.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'As for the priests, the descendants of Aaron, who were living in
        the open villages around the towns, men were appointed by name to distribute
        portions to every male among the priests and to all the Levites listed in
        the genealogical records.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'In this way, King Hezekiah handled the distribution throughout all
        Judah, doing what was pleasing and good in the sight of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        his God. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "In all that he did in the service of the Temple of God and in his
        efforts to follow God\u2019s laws and commands, Hezekiah sought his God wholeheartedly.
        As a result, he was very successful."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Assyria Invades Judah'
      title: Assyria Invades Judah
      number: 1
      content: '  After Hezekiah had faithfully carried out this work, King Sennacherib
        of Assyria invaded Judah. He laid siege to the fortified towns, giving orders
        for his army to break through their walls. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'When Hezekiah realized that Sennacherib also intended to attack Jerusalem, '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'he consulted with his officials and military advisers, and they decided
        to stop the flow of the springs outside the city. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "They organized a huge work crew to stop the flow of the springs,
        cutting off the brook that ran through the fields. For they said, \u201CWhy
        should the kings of Assyria come here and find plenty of water?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Then Hezekiah worked hard at repairing all the broken sections of
        the wall, erecting towers, and constructing a second wall outside the first.
        He also reinforced the supporting terraces[[COMMENT(0)]] in the City of David
        and manufactured large numbers of weapons and shields. '
      comments:
      - number: '32:5 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the millo. </b>The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'He appointed military officers over the people and assembled them
        before him in the square at the city gate. Then Hezekiah encouraged them
        by saying: '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "\u201CBe strong and courageous! Don\u2019t be afraid or discouraged
        because of the king of Assyria or his mighty army, for there is a power far
        greater on our side! "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: Sennacherib Threatens Jerusalem'
      title: Sennacherib Threatens Jerusalem
      number: 8
      content: "He may have a great army, but they are merely men. We have the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        our God to help us and to fight our battles for us!\u201D Hezekiah\u2019s
        words greatly encouraged the people.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'While King Sennacherib of Assyria was still besieging the town of
        Lachish, he sent his officers to Jerusalem with this message for Hezekiah
        and all the people in the city:  '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201CThis is what King Sennacherib of Assyria says: What are you
        trusting in that makes you think you can survive my siege of Jerusalem? "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Hezekiah has said, \u2018The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> our God
        will rescue us from the king of Assyria.\u2019 Surely Hezekiah is misleading
        you, sentencing you to death by famine and thirst! "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Don\u2019t you realize that Hezekiah is the very person who destroyed
        all the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s shrines and altars? He commanded
        Judah and Jerusalem to worship only at the altar at the Temple and to offer
        sacrifices on it alone.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201CSurely you must realize what I and the other kings of Assyria
        before me have done to all the people of the earth! Were any of the gods
        of those nations able to rescue their people from my power? "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Which of their gods was able to rescue its people from the destructive
        power of my predecessors? What makes you think your God can rescue you from
        me? '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Don\u2019t let Hezekiah deceive you! Don\u2019t let him fool you
        like this! I say it again\u2014no god of any nation or kingdom has ever yet
        been able to rescue his people from me or my ancestors. How much less will
        your God rescue you from my power!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "And Sennacherib\u2019s officers further mocked the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        God and his servant Hezekiah, heaping insult upon insult. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "The king also sent letters scorning the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel. He wrote, \u201CJust as the gods of all the other nations
        failed to rescue their people from my power, so the God of Hezekiah will
        also fail.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'The Assyrian officials who brought the letters shouted this in Hebrew[[COMMENT(0)]]
        to the people gathered on the walls of the city, trying to terrify them so
        it would be easier to capture the city. '
      comments:
      - number: '32:18 '
        content: Hebrew <b>in the dialect of Judah.</b>
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'These officers talked about the God of Jerusalem as though he were
        one of the pagan gods, made by human hands.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Then King Hezekiah and the prophet Isaiah son of Amoz cried out in
        prayer to God in heaven. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> sent an angel who destroyed the
        Assyrian army with all its commanders and officers. So Sennacherib was forced
        to return home in disgrace to his own land. And when he entered the temple
        of his god, some of his own sons killed him there with a sword.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'That is how the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> rescued Hezekiah and
        the people of Jerusalem from King Sennacherib of Assyria and from all the
        others who threatened them. So there was peace throughout the land. '
      comments: []
    - name: "23: Hezekiah\u2019s Sickness and Recovery"
      title: "Hezekiah\u2019s Sickness and Recovery"
      number: 23
      content: 'From then on King Hezekiah became highly respected among all the
        surrounding nations, and many gifts for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> arrived
        at Jerusalem, with valuable presents for King Hezekiah, too.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'About that time Hezekiah became deathly ill. He prayed to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        who healed him and gave him a miraculous sign. '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "But Hezekiah did not respond appropriately to the kindness shown
        him, and he became proud. So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s anger
        came against him and against Judah and Jerusalem. "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "Then Hezekiah humbled himself and repented of his pride, as did the
        people of Jerusalem. So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s anger did
        not fall on them during Hezekiah\u2019s lifetime.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'Hezekiah was very wealthy and highly honored. He built special treasury
        buildings for his silver, gold, precious stones, and spices, and for his
        shields and other valuable items. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'He also constructed many storehouses for his grain, new wine, and
        olive oil; and he made many stalls for his cattle and pens for his flocks
        of sheep and goats. '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'He built many towns and acquired vast flocks and herds, for God had
        given him great wealth. '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'He blocked up the upper spring of Gihon and brought the water down
        through a tunnel to the west side of the City of David. And so he succeeded
        in everything he did.  '
      comments: []
    - name: "31: Summary of Hezekiah\u2019s Reign"
      title: "Summary of Hezekiah\u2019s Reign"
      number: 31
      content: 'However, when ambassadors arrived from Babylon to ask about the remarkable
        events that had taken place in the land, God withdrew from Hezekiah in order
        to test him and to see what was really in his heart.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "The rest of the events in Hezekiah\u2019s reign and his acts of devotion
        are recorded in The Vision of the Prophet Isaiah Son of Amoz, which is included
        in The Book of the Kings of Judah and Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: When Hezekiah died, he was buried in the upper area of the royal cemetery,
        and all Judah and Jerusalem honored him at his death. And his son Manasseh
        became the next king.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Manasseh Rules in Judah'
      title: Manasseh Rules in Judah
      number: 1
      content: '  Manasseh was twelve years old when he became king, and he reigned
        in Jerusalem fifty-five years. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "He did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s sight,
        following the detestable practices of the pagan nations that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had driven from the land ahead of the Israelites. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'He rebuilt the pagan shrines his father, Hezekiah, had broken down.
        He constructed altars for the images of Baal and set up Asherah poles. He
        also bowed before all the powers of the heavens and worshiped them.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "He built pagan altars in the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the place where the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had said, \u201CMy name will
        remain in Jerusalem forever.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "He built these altars for all the powers of the heavens in both courtyards
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Manasseh also sacrificed his own sons in the fire[[COMMENT(0)]] in
        the valley of Ben-Hinnom. He practiced sorcery, divination, and witchcraft,
        and he consulted with mediums and psychics. He did much that was evil in
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s sight, arousing his anger.  "
      comments:
      - number: '33:6 '
        content: Or <b>also made his sons pass through the fire.</b>
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Manasseh even took a carved idol he had made and set it up in God\u2019s
        Temple, the very place where God had told David and his son Solomon: \u201CMy
        name will be honored forever in this Temple and in Jerusalem\u2014the city
        I have chosen from among all the tribes of Israel. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "If the Israelites will be careful to obey my commands\u2014all the
        laws, decrees, and regulations given through Moses\u2014I will not send them
        into exile from this land that I set aside for your ancestors.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'But Manasseh led the people of Judah and Jerusalem to do even more
        evil than the pagan nations that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had destroyed
        when the people of Israel entered the land.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> spoke to Manasseh and his people,
        but they ignored all his warnings. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> sent the commanders of the Assyrian
        armies, and they took Manasseh prisoner. They put a ring through his nose,
        bound him in bronze chains, and led him away to Babylon. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'But while in deep distress, Manasseh sought the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        his God and sincerely humbled himself before the God of his ancestors. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'And when he prayed, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> listened to him
        and was moved by his request. So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> brought
        Manasseh back to Jerusalem and to his kingdom. Then Manasseh finally realized
        that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> alone is God!  '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'After this Manasseh rebuilt the outer wall of the City of David,
        from west of the Gihon Spring in the Kidron Valley to the Fish Gate, and
        continuing around the hill of Ophel. He built the wall very high. And he
        stationed his military officers in all of the fortified towns of Judah. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Manasseh also removed the foreign gods and the idol from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple. He tore down all the altars he had built on the hill where the Temple
        stood and all the altars that were in Jerusalem, and he dumped them outside
        the city. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Then he restored the altar of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and
        sacrificed peace offerings and thanksgiving offerings on it. He also encouraged
        the people of Judah to worship the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of
        Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'However, the people still sacrificed at the pagan shrines, though
        only to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> their God.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "The rest of the events of Manasseh\u2019s reign, his prayer to God,
        and the words the seers spoke to him in the name of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel, are recorded in The Book of the Kings of Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Manasseh\u2019s prayer, the account of the way God answered him,
        and an account of all his sins and unfaithfulness are recorded in The Record
        of the Seers.[[COMMENT(0)]] It includes a list of the locations where he
        built pagan shrines and set up Asherah poles and idols before he humbled
        himself and repented. "
      comments:
      - number: '33:19 '
        content: Or <b>The Record of Hozai.</b>
    - name: '20: Amon Rules in Judah'
      title: Amon Rules in Judah
      number: 20
      content: 'When Manasseh died, he was buried in his palace. Then his son Amon
        became the next king.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'Amon was twenty-two years old when he became king, and he reigned
        in Jerusalem two years. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "He did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s sight,
        just as his father, Manasseh, had done. He worshiped and sacrificed to all
        the idols his father had made. "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'But unlike his father, he did not humble himself before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        Instead, Amon sinned even more.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Then Amon\u2019s own officials conspired against him and assassinated
        him in his palace. "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: But the people of the land killed all those who had conspired against
        King Amon, and they made his son Josiah the next king.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Josiah Rules in Judah'
      title: Josiah Rules in Judah
      number: 1
      content: '  Josiah was eight years old when he became king, and he reigned
        in Jerusalem thirty-one years. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "He did what was pleasing in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight and followed the example of his ancestor David. He did not turn away
        from doing what was right.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'During the eighth year of his reign, while he was still young, Josiah
        began to seek the God of his ancestor David. Then in the twelfth year he
        began to purify Judah and Jerusalem, destroying all the pagan shrines, the
        Asherah poles, and the carved idols and cast images. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'He ordered that the altars of Baal be demolished and that the incense
        altars which stood above them be broken down. He also made sure that the
        Asherah poles, the carved idols, and the cast images were smashed and scattered
        over the graves of those who had sacrificed to them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'He burned the bones of the pagan priests on their own altars, and
        so he purified Judah and Jerusalem.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'He did the same thing in the towns of Manasseh, Ephraim, and Simeon,
        even as far as Naphtali, and in the regions[[COMMENT(0)]] all around them. '
      comments:
      - number: '34:6 '
        content: As in Syriac version; Hebrew reads <b>in their temples, </b>or <b>in
          their ruins. </b>The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'He destroyed the pagan altars and the Asherah poles, and he crushed
        the idols into dust. He cut down all the incense altars throughout the land
        of Israel. Finally, he returned to Jerusalem.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'In the eighteenth year of his reign, after he had purified the land
        and the Temple, Josiah appointed Shaphan son of Azaliah, Maaseiah the governor
        of Jerusalem, and Joah son of Joahaz, the royal historian, to repair the
        Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> his God. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'They gave Hilkiah the high priest the money that had been collected
        by the Levites who served as gatekeepers at the Temple of God. The gifts
        were brought by people from Manasseh, Ephraim, and from all the remnant of
        Israel, as well as from all Judah, Benjamin, and the people of Jerusalem.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "He entrusted the money to the men assigned to supervise the restoration
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple. Then they paid the workers
        who did the repairs and renovation of the Temple. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'They hired carpenters and builders, who purchased finished stone
        for the walls and timber for the rafters and beams. They restored what earlier
        kings of Judah had allowed to fall into ruin.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'The workers served faithfully under the leadership of Jahath and
        Obadiah, Levites of the Merarite clan, and Zechariah and Meshullam, Levites
        of the Kohathite clan. Other Levites, all of whom were skilled musicians, '
      comments: []
    - name: "13: Hilkiah Discovers God\u2019s Law"
      title: "Hilkiah Discovers God\u2019s Law"
      number: 13
      content: 'were put in charge of the laborers of the various trades. Still others
        assisted as secretaries, officials, and gatekeepers.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "While they were bringing out the money collected at the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple, Hilkiah the priest found the Book of the Law of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        that was written by Moses. "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Hilkiah said to Shaphan the court secretary, \u201CI have found the
        Book of the Law in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple!\u201D Then
        Hilkiah gave the scroll to Shaphan.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Shaphan took the scroll to the king and reported, \u201CYour officials
        are doing everything they were assigned to do. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "The money that was collected at the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has been turned over to the supervisors and workmen.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Shaphan also told the king, \u201CHilkiah the priest has given me
        a scroll.\u201D So Shaphan read it to the king.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'When the king heard what was written in the Law, he tore his clothes
        in despair. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Then he gave these orders to Hilkiah, Ahikam son of Shaphan, Acbor
        son of Micaiah,[[COMMENT(0)]] Shaphan the court secretary, and Asaiah the
        king\u2019s personal adviser: "
      comments:
      - number: '34:20 '
        content: As in parallel text at 2 Kgs 22:12; Hebrew reads <b>Abdon son of
          Micah.</b>
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "\u201CGo to the Temple and speak to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        for me and for all the remnant of Israel and Judah. Inquire about the words
        written in the scroll that has been found. For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        great anger has been poured out on us because our ancestors have not obeyed
        the word of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. We have not been doing everything
        this scroll says we must do.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'So Hilkiah and the other men went to the New Quarter[[COMMENT(0)]]
        of Jerusalem to consult with the prophet Huldah. She was the wife of Shallum
        son of Tikvah, son of Harhas,[[COMMENT(1)]] the keeper of the Temple wardrobe.  '
      comments:
      - number: '34:22a '
        content: Or <b>the Second Quarter, </b>a newer section of Jerusalem. Hebrew
          reads <b>the Mishneh.</b>
      - number: '34:22b '
        content: As in parallel text at 2 Kgs 22:14; Hebrew reads <b>son of Tokhath,
          son of Hasrah.</b>
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "She said to them, \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God
        of Israel, has spoken! Go back and tell the man who sent you, "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "\u2018This is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: I am going
        to bring disaster on this city[[COMMENT(0)]] and its people. All the curses
        written in the scroll that was read to the king of Judah will come true. "
      comments:
      - number: '34:24 '
        content: Hebrew <b>this place; </b>also in 34:27, 28.
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "For my people have abandoned me and offered sacrifices to pagan gods,
        and I am very angry with them for everything they have done. My anger will
        be poured out on this place, and it will not be quenched.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "\u201CBut go to the king of Judah who sent you to seek the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and tell him: \u2018This is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God
        of Israel, says concerning the message you have just heard: "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'You were sorry and humbled yourself before God when you heard his
        words against this city and its people. You humbled yourself and tore your
        clothing in despair and wept before me in repentance. And I have indeed heard
        you, says the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: "28: Josiah\u2019s Religious Reforms"
      title: "Josiah\u2019s Religious Reforms"
      number: 28
      content: "So I will not send the promised disaster until after you have died
        and been buried in peace. You yourself will not see the disaster I am going
        to bring on this city and its people.\u2019\u201DSo they took her message
        back to the king.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'Then the king summoned all the elders of Judah and Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "And the king went up to the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        with all the people of Judah and Jerusalem, along with the priests and the
        Levites\u2014all the people from the greatest to the least. There the king
        read to them the entire Book of the Covenant that had been found in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple. "
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "The king took his place of authority beside the pillar and renewed
        the covenant in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s presence. He pledged
        to obey the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> by keeping all his commands, laws,
        and decrees with all his heart and soul. He promised to obey all the terms
        of the covenant that were written in the scroll. "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'And he required everyone in Jerusalem and the people of Benjamin
        to make a similar pledge. The people of Jerusalem did so, renewing their
        covenant with God, the God of their ancestors.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: So Josiah removed all detestable idols from the entire land of Israel
        and required everyone to worship the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> their God.
        And throughout the rest of his lifetime, they did not turn away from the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of their ancestors.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Josiah Celebrates Passover'
      title: Josiah Celebrates Passover
      number: 1
      content: '  Then Josiah announced that the Passover of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        would be celebrated in Jerusalem, and so the Passover lamb was slaughtered
        on the fourteenth day of the first month.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '35:1 '
        content: This day in the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar was April 5, 622 <span
          class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Josiah also assigned the priests to their duties and encouraged them
        in their work at the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "He issued this order to the Levites, who were to teach all Israel
        and who had been set apart to serve the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: \u201CPut
        the holy Ark in the Temple that was built by Solomon son of David, the king
        of Israel. You no longer need to carry it back and forth on your shoulders.
        Now spend your time serving the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God and
        his people Israel. "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'Report for duty according to the family divisions of your ancestors,
        following the directions of King David of Israel and the directions of his
        son Solomon.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "\u201CThen stand in the sanctuary at the place appointed for your
        family division and help the families assigned to you as they bring their
        offerings to the Temple. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Slaughter the Passover lambs, purify yourselves, and prepare to help
        those who come. Follow all the directions that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        gave through Moses.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Then Josiah provided 30,000 lambs and young goats for the people\u2019s
        Passover offerings, along with 3,000 cattle, all from the king\u2019s own
        flocks and herds. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "The king\u2019s officials also made willing contributions to the
        people, priests, and Levites. Hilkiah, Zechariah, and Jehiel, the administrators
        of God\u2019s Temple, gave the priests 2,600 lambs and young goats and 300
        cattle as Passover offerings. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "The Levite leaders\u2014Conaniah and his brothers Shemaiah and Nethanel,
        as well as Hashabiah, Jeiel, and Jozabad\u2014gave 5,000 lambs and young
        goats and 500 cattle to the Levites for their Passover offerings.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'When everything was ready for the Passover celebration, the priests
        and the Levites took their places, organized by their divisions, as the king
        had commanded. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'The Levites then slaughtered the Passover lambs and presented the
        blood to the priests, who sprinkled the blood on the altar while the Levites
        prepared the animals. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'They divided the burnt offerings among the people by their family
        groups, so they could offer them to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> as prescribed
        in the Book of Moses. They did the same with the cattle. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Then they roasted the Passover lambs as prescribed; and they boiled
        the holy offerings in pots, kettles, and pans, and brought them out quickly
        so the people could eat them.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Afterward the Levites prepared Passover offerings for themselves
        and for the priests\u2014the descendants of Aaron\u2014because the priests
        had been busy from morning till night offering the burnt offerings and the
        fat portions. The Levites took responsibility for all these preparations.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "The musicians, descendants of Asaph, were in their assigned places,
        following the commands that had been given by David, Asaph, Heman, and Jeduthun,
        the king\u2019s seer. The gatekeepers guarded the gates and did not need
        to leave their posts of duty, for their Passover offerings were prepared
        for them by their fellow Levites.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "The entire ceremony for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Passover
        was completed that day. All the burnt offerings were sacrificed on the altar
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, as King Josiah had commanded. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'All the Israelites present in Jerusalem celebrated Passover and the
        Festival of Unleavened Bread for seven days. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Never since the time of the prophet Samuel had there been such a
        Passover. None of the kings of Israel had ever kept a Passover as Josiah
        did, involving all the priests and Levites, all the people of Jerusalem,
        and people from all over Judah and Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: Josiah Dies in Battle'
      title: Josiah Dies in Battle
      number: 19
      content: "This Passover was celebrated in the eighteenth year of Josiah\u2019s
        reign.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'After Josiah had finished restoring the Temple, King Neco of Egypt
        led his army up from Egypt to do battle at Carchemish on the Euphrates River,
        and Josiah and his army marched out to fight him.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '35:20 '
        content: Or <b>Josiah went out to meet him.</b>
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "But King Neco sent messengers to Josiah with this message:\u201CWhat
        do you want with me, king of Judah? I have no quarrel with you today! I am
        on my way to fight another nation, and God has told me to hurry! Do not interfere
        with God, who is with me, or he will destroy you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'But Josiah refused to listen to Neco, to whom God had indeed spoken,
        and he would not turn back. Instead, he disguised himself and led his army
        into battle on the plain of Megiddo. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "But the enemy archers hit King Josiah with their arrows and wounded
        him. He cried out to his men, \u201CTake me from the battle, for I am badly
        wounded!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'So they lifted Josiah out of his chariot and placed him in another
        chariot. Then they brought him back to Jerusalem, where he died. He was buried
        there in the royal cemetery. And all Judah and Jerusalem mourned for him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'The prophet Jeremiah composed funeral songs for Josiah, and to this
        day choirs still sing these sad songs about his death. These songs of sorrow
        have become a tradition and are recorded in The Book of Laments.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "The rest of the events of Josiah\u2019s reign and his acts of devotion
        (carried out according to what was written in the Law of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>), "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "from beginning to end\u2014all are recorded in The Book of the Kings
        of Israel and Judah."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Jehoahaz Rules in Judah'
      title: Jehoahaz Rules in Judah
      number: 1
      content: "  Then the people of the land took Josiah\u2019s son Jehoahaz and
        made him the next king in Jerusalem.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Jehoahaz[[COMMENT(0)]] was twenty-three years old when he became
        king, and he reigned in Jerusalem three months.  '
      comments:
      - number: '36:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Joahaz, </b>a variant spelling of Jehoahaz; also in 36:4.
    - name: '3: Jehoiakim Rules in Judah'
      title: Jehoiakim Rules in Judah
      number: 3
      content: 'Then he was deposed by the king of Egypt, who demanded that Judah
        pay 7,500 pounds of silver and 75 pounds of gold[[COMMENT(0)]] as tribute.  '
      comments:
      - number: '36:3 '
        content: Hebrew <b>100 talents </b>[3,400 kilograms] <b>of silver and 1 talent
          </b>[34 kilograms] <b>of gold.</b>
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "The king of Egypt then installed Eliakim, the brother of Jehoahaz,
        as the next king of Judah and Jerusalem, and he changed Eliakim\u2019s name
        to Jehoiakim. Then Neco took Jehoahaz to Egypt as a prisoner.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Jehoiakim was twenty-five years old when he became king, and he reigned
        in Jerusalem eleven years. He did what was evil in the sight of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        his God.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Then King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon came to Jerusalem and captured
        it, and he bound Jehoiakim in bronze chains and led him away to Babylon. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Nebuchadnezzar also took some of the treasures from the Temple of
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, and he placed them in his palace[[COMMENT(0)]]
        in Babylon.  '
      comments:
      - number: '36:7 '
        content: Or <b>temple.</b>
    - name: '8: Jehoiachin Rules in Judah'
      title: Jehoiachin Rules in Judah
      number: 8
      content: "The rest of the events in Jehoiakim\u2019s reign, including all the
        evil things he did and everything found against him, are recorded in The
        Book of the Kings of Israel and Judah. Then his son Jehoiachin became the
        next king.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Jehoiachin was eighteen[[COMMENT(0)]] years old when he became king,
        and he reigned in Jerusalem three months and ten days. Jehoiachin did what
        was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s sight.  "
      comments:
      - number: '36:9 '
        content: As in one Hebrew manuscript, some Greek manuscripts, and Syriac
          version (see also 2 Kgs 24:8); most Hebrew manuscripts read <b>eight.</b>
    - name: '10: Zedekiah Rules in Judah'
      title: Zedekiah Rules in Judah
      number: 10
      content: "In the spring of the year[[COMMENT(0)]] King Nebuchadnezzar took
        Jehoiachin to Babylon. Many treasures from the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        were also taken to Babylon at that time. And Nebuchadnezzar installed Jehoiachin\u2019s
        uncle,[[COMMENT(1)]] Zedekiah, as the next king in Judah and Jerusalem.  "
      comments:
      - number: '36:10a '
        content: Hebrew <b>At the turn of the year. </b>The first day of this year
          in the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar was April 13, 597 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>
      - number: '36:10b '
        content: As in parallel text at 2 Kgs 24:17; Hebrew reads <b>brother, </b>or
          <b>relative.</b>
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Zedekiah was twenty-one years old when he became king, and he reigned
        in Jerusalem eleven years. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'But Zedekiah did what was evil in the sight of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        his God, and he refused to humble himself when the prophet Jeremiah spoke
        to him directly from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "He also rebelled against King Nebuchadnezzar, even though he had
        taken an oath of loyalty in God\u2019s name. Zedekiah was a hard and stubborn
        man, refusing to turn to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Likewise, all the leaders of the priests and the people became more
        and more unfaithful. They followed all the pagan practices of the surrounding
        nations, desecrating the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> that had
        been consecrated in Jerusalem.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of their ancestors, repeatedly
        sent his prophets to warn them, for he had compassion on his people and his
        Temple. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: The Fall of Jerusalem'
      title: The Fall of Jerusalem
      number: 16
      content: "But the people mocked these messengers of God and despised their
        words. They scoffed at the prophets until the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        anger could no longer be restrained and nothing could be done.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> brought the king of Babylon against
        them. The Babylonians[[COMMENT(0)]] killed Judah\u2019s young men, even chasing
        after them into the Temple. They had no pity on the people, killing both
        young men and young women, the old and the infirm. God handed all of them
        over to Nebuchadnezzar. "
      comments:
      - number: '36:17 '
        content: Or <b>Chaldeans.</b>
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "The king took home to Babylon all the articles, large and small,
        used in the Temple of God, and the treasures from both the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple and from the palace of the king and his officials. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'Then his army burned the Temple of God, tore down the walls of Jerusalem,
        burned all the palaces, and completely destroyed everything of value.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '36:19 '
        content: Or <b>destroyed all the valuable articles from the Temple.</b>
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'The few who survived were taken as exiles to Babylon, and they became
        servants to the king and his sons until the kingdom of Persia came to power.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: Cyrus Allows the Exiles to Return'
      title: Cyrus Allows the Exiles to Return
      number: 21
      content: 'So the message of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> spoken through
        Jeremiah was fulfilled. The land finally enjoyed its Sabbath rest, lying
        desolate until the seventy years were fulfilled, just as the prophet had
        said.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'In the first year of King Cyrus of Persia,[[COMMENT(0)]] the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        fulfilled the prophecy he had given through Jeremiah.[[COMMENT(1)]] He stirred
        the heart of Cyrus to put this proclamation in writing and to send it throughout
        his kingdom:  '
      comments:
      - number: '36:22a '
        content: "The first year of Cyrus\u2019s reign over Babylon was 538 <span
          class=\"ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da\">b.c.</span>"
      - number: '36:22b '
        content: See Jer 25:11-12; 29:10.
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "\u201CThis is what King Cyrus of Persia says:\u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of heaven, has given me all the kingdoms of the earth. He has appointed
        me to build him a Temple at Jerusalem, which is in Judah. Any of you who
        are his people may go there for this task. And may the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God be with you!\u201D"
      comments: []
